{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HGTGnmtYSNwSRZfzpcmEjK","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Iteration 30 â†’ 31 Improvement Plan\n     2â†’\n     3â†’**Status:** Draft\n     4â†’**Date:** 2026-03-17\n     5â†’**Baseline:** 91.9% combined accuracy (9 failures, all generated; 0 real failures)\n     6â†’\n     7â†’---\n     8â†’\n     9â†’## Overview\n    10â†’\n    11â†’Iteration 30 implemented all 6 changes from the iter 29 plan (OCR repair, garbled detection, Polish verbs, positional bonus). Yet the same 9 failures persist. The iter 29 analysis was correct about downstream symptoms but missed the true root cause for 6 of 9 failures.\n    12â†’\n    13â†’**The primary root cause is the continuation-line merge in `buildCandidates`** (lines 646â€“658). The merge treats `(` as a continuation character, so any parenthetical annotation line immediately following the title gets merged with it. The merged result fails the â‰¥8-word or â‰¥80-char hard filter, and the original single-line title is never generated as a candidate. All iter 29 fixes (OCR repair, cooking verb detection) were correct but never had a chance to fire because the title was destroyed before candidate generation.\n    14â†’\n    15â†’---\n    16â†’\n    17â†’## Root Cause Deep Dive\n    18â†’\n    19â†’### The continuation merge bug (6/9 failures)\n    20â†’\n    21â†’`buildCandidates` pre-merges continuation lines (lines 646â€“658):\n    22â†’\n    23â†’```typescript\n    24â†’if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n    25â†’  mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n    26â†’  i++;  // â†گ skips nextText AND loses the original line.text as a standalone\n    27â†’  continue;\n    28â†’}\n    29â†’```\n    30â†’\n    31â†’The regex `^[/&+:(]` is designed for real continuations like `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS` + `/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`. But it also matches the synthetic `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` annotation lines that the test generator places on line 3 of each generated file.\n    32â†’\n    33â†’**Trace for \"Braised Cod with White Wine\":**\n    34â†’\n    35â†’1. Non-empty lines: `[0] Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`, `[1] (OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation)`, `[2] lngredients:`\n    36â†’2. Continuation merge: line `[1]` starts with `(` â†’ merged with `[0]`\n    37â†’3. Merged text: `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne (OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation)` (11 words)\n    38â†’4. `repairOcrText` â†’ `Braised Cod with White Wine (OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation)`\n    39â†’5. `passesHardFilters`: fails `words.length >= 8` check â†’ rejected\n    40â†’6. The original standalone `Braised Cod with White Wine` was never generated\n    41â†’\n    42â†’**Same mechanism for:** Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip, Droإ¼dإ¼e Sernik, Piernik z إڑliwkami, إ»urek Krakowski (5 more cases, all have `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` on line 3).\n    43â†’\n    44â†’### Remaining root causes (3/9 failures)\n    45â†’\n    46â†’| Pattern | Case | Root cause |\n    47â†’|---------|------|-----------|\n    48â†’| C: Partial OCR normalization | Sole with Brown Butter and Capers | `sole` not in food dictionary; blind repair maps `01â†’oi` (i-variant) instead of `0â†’o, 1â†’l` (l-variant). No annotation merge issue â€” file has no `(OCR ...)` line. |\n    49â†’| D: Erratic casing + `آ،` | Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leإ›nymi | No merge issue (line 2 is regular text). The erratic-casing normalization + blind `آ،â†’i` repair should produce `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leإ›nymi` as a candidate. Issue is downstream: the cooking instruction `Ugotuj ziemniaky.` (2 words) passes the `looksLikeCookingInstruction` word-count guard (requires â‰¥4) and outscores the title. |\n    50â†’| E: Metadata â†’ empty | Ogأ³rkowa Zupa | Pipe-separated metadata filtered correctly, `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` should be candidate. MiniLM gives weak score for Polish ALL_CAPS; positional bonus cap may be too low. |\n    51â†’| F: Title absent | Mushroom Risotto | Title doesn't appear in document. Not fixable without external context. |\n    52â†’\n    53â†’---\n    54â†’\n    55â†’## Goals\n    56â†’\n    57â†’- Fix the 6 continuation-merge failures (Patterns A, B: all files with `(OCR ...)` annotations)\n    58â†’- Fix Pattern C (Sole: dictionary gap)\n    59â†’- Fix Pattern D (Kopytka: short cooking instruction not caught)\n    60â†’- Fix Pattern E (Ogأ³rkowa Zupa: Polish ALL_CAPS weak embedding)\n    61â†’- Maintain 100% accuracy on real files\n    62â†’- No regressions on currently-passing generated files\n    63â†’- Keep total extraction time under 10 seconds on device\n    64â†’\n    65â†’## Non-Goals\n    66â†’\n    67â†’- Fix Pattern F (Mushroom Risotto: title absent from document) â€” requires page-level context\n    68â†’- Change the embedding model â€” MiniLM works well for 102+ passing cases\n    69â†’- Restructure the full candidate generation pipeline â€” only the merge logic needs fixing\n    70â†’\n    71â†’---\n    72â†’\n    73â†’## Detailed Changes\n    74â†’\n    75â†’### Change 1: Preserve standalone candidate when continuation-merging\n    76â†’\n    77â†’**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, lines 646â€“658\n    78â†’\n    79â†’**Problem:** The continuation merge replaces the original line with the merged form and skips ahead. The original short form is never added to `mergedLines`, so it can never become a candidate.\n    80â†’\n    81â†’**Fix:** Always emit the original line as well as the merged form. The downstream `seen` set in the candidate loop (line 661) will deduplicate if both forms produce the same normalized text.\n    82â†’\n    83â†’```typescript\n    84â†’for (let i = 0; i < capsCoalesced.length; i++) {\n    85â†’  const line = capsCoalesced[i];\n    86â†’  mergedLines.push(line);  // â†گ always keep the original\n    87â†’  if (i + 1 < capsCoalesced.length) {\n    88â†’    const nextText = capsCoalesced[i + 1].text;\n    89â†’    if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n    90â†’      mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n    91â†’      i++;\n    92â†’      continue;\n    93â†’    }\n    94â†’  }\n    95â†’}\n    96â†’```\n    97â†’\n    98â†’**Why this is safe:** The `seen` set deduplicates by normalized text. If both the standalone and the merge produce passing candidates, both enter the pool â€” the dedup and scoring logic downstream picks the better one. If the merge fails hard filters (as in the annotation case), only the standalone survives. If the standalone fails (rare â€” means the line is truly garbled), the merge might still pass. This is strictly more capable than the current approach.\n    99â†’\n   100â†’**Risk assessment:** Low. The continuation merge was designed for cases like `TITLE / SUBTITLE` where the `/` line is meaningless on its own. In those cases, the standalone `TITLE` will still be generated AND the merge `TITLE / SUBTITLE` will also be generated. The existing dedup, prefix-removal, and multi-title logic handles this correctly â€” the test for `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE` already has the prefix-removal step that eliminates the standalone when the merge is better.\n   101â†’\n   102â†’**Impact:** Directly fixes 6 of 9 failures. After this change, `Braised Cod with White Wine` enters the candidate pool as a standalone, gets dictionary-repaired, scores well against the title embedding, and is selected.\n   103â†’\n   104â†’**Cross-iteration note:** This is NOT the same as \"removing the continuation merge\" â€” the merge still runs and produces joined candidates. It's adding the standalone alongside it. The merge was introduced in iter 16 to fix fragmented titles; this change preserves that behavior while preventing annotation-merge destruction.\n   105â†’\n   106â†’---\n   107â†’\n   108â†’### Change 2: Add \"sole\" and related fish names to the food dictionary\n   109â†’\n   110â†’**File:** `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n   111â†’\n   112â†’**Problem:** `S01e with Brown Butter and Capers` â€” `sole` is not in the food dictionary, so dictionary-guided repair can't resolve the ambiguity. The blind repair produces `Soie` (0â†’o, 1â†’i) instead of `Sole` (0â†’o, 1â†’l).\n   113â†’\n   114â†’**Fix:** Add missing common fish/food names to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`:\n   115â†’\n   116â†’```typescript\n   117â†’\"sole\",     // flatfish â€” needed for \"S01e\" OCR repair\n   118â†’\"soie\",     // NOT a food word â€” do not add (French for silk)\n   119â†’```\n   120â†’\n   121â†’With `sole` in the dictionary, `repairOcrWord(\"S01e\")` generates candidates including `sole` (0â†’o, 1â†’l), finds it in the dictionary, and returns `Sole`.\n   122â†’\n   123â†’**Impact:** Directly fixes Pattern C. The title becomes `Sole with Brown Butter and Capers` instead of `Soie with Brown Butter and Capers`.\n   124â†’\n   125â†’**Risk:** None. `sole` is unambiguously a food item in the context of recipe text.\n   126â†’\n   127â†’---\n   128â†’\n   129â†’### Change 3: Lower word-count threshold for cooking instruction detection\n   130â†’\n   131â†’**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `looksLikeCookingInstruction` (line 364)\n   132â†’\n   133â†’**Problem:** `Ugotuj ziemniaky.` (2 words) passes through the cooking instruction filter because the guard requires `words.length >= 4`. This 2-word cooking instruction then enters the candidate pool and outscores the title `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leإ›nymi`.\n   134â†’\n   135â†’The `>= 4` threshold was originally set to prevent short recipe titles like `Roast Chicken` or `Grilled Salmon` from being falsely classified as cooking instructions. But it's too permissive â€” `Ugotuj ziemniaky.` and `Upiecz chleb.` are clearly instructions, not titles.\n   136â†’\n   137â†’**Fix:** Split the word-count guard by language:\n   138â†’\n   139â†’```typescript\n   140â†’function looksLikeCookingInstruction(text: string): boolean {\n   141â†’  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n   142â†’  // English cooking instructions are typically â‰¥4 words (\"Roast the chicken until...\")\n   143â†’  // but short English imperatives can also be recipe titles (\"Roast Chicken\", \"Grilled Salmon\").\n   144â†’  // Polish cooking instructions are commonly 2-3 words (\"Ugotuj ziemniaki.\", \"Upiecz chleb.\")\n   145â†’  // and are unambiguous because Polish recipe titles don't start with imperative verbs.\n   146â†’  if (POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) {\n   147â†’    return words.length >= 2;  // Polish: 2+ words is enough\n   148â†’  }\n   149â†’  if (words.length < 4) return false;  // English: keep existing 4-word threshold\n   150â†’  if (COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\n   151â†’  return false;\n   152â†’}\n   153â†’```\n   154â†’\n   155â†’**Why this is safe for Polish but not English:**\n   156â†’- Polish recipe titles never start with bare imperative verbs. The title is always a noun phrase: `Piernik z إڑliwkami`, `Kopytka z Pieczarkami`, `إ»urek Krakowski`. The cooking section uses imperatives: `Ugotuj`, `Podawaj`, `Dodaj`.\n   157â†’- English recipe titles CAN start with the same words as cooking instructions: `Roast Chicken` (title) vs `Roast the chicken` (instruction). The 4-word guard protects these.\n   158â†’\n   159â†’**Impact:** Fixes Pattern D. `Ugotuj ziemniaky.` is now caught as a cooking instruction, never enters the candidate pool. The title `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leإ›nymi` (after erratic-casing normalization and `آ،â†’i` repair) wins.\n   160â†’\n   161â†’**Risk:** Low. Polish imperative verbs at the start of a line are unambiguously instructions. No Polish recipe title in the test suite or in common cookbook conventions starts with an imperative verb.\n   162â†’\n   163â†’---\n   164â†’\n   165â†’### Change 4: Strengthen Polish ALL_CAPS positional signal for pipe-metadata preamble\n   166â†’\n   167â†’**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, positional bonus logic (lines ~1230â€“1246)\n   168â†’\n   169â†’**Problem:** `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` appears after a pipe-separated metadata line. The candidate enters the pool and gets the pipe-preamble positional bonus (+0.12), the direct-successor bonus (+0.10), but the combined boost is capped at 0.18 (the pipe+ALL_CAPS special cap from iter 30). MiniLM gives a weak raw embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS text (likely near 0 or slightly negative), so even with +0.18 boost, the candidate may fall below the threshold.\n   170â†’\n   171â†’**Investigation:** The iter 29 plan already raised the cap from 0.15 to 0.18 for pipe+ALL_CAPS. If 0.18 is still insufficient, there are two options:\n   172â†’\n   173â†’**Option A (preferred): Raise the cap to 0.22 for pipe+ALL_CAPS.** The pipe-metadata + ALL_CAPS pattern is a near-certain title indicator in Polish cookbooks. The extra 0.04 headroom accounts for MiniLM's English bias.\n   174â†’\n   175â†’**Option B: Lower the rawScore floor for pipe+ALL_CAPS candidates.** Currently the fallback path requires `rawScore > -0.05` for early-position candidates. For pipe+ALL_CAPS, this could be relaxed to `-0.10`. But this is riskier â€” it allows weaker candidates through.\n   176â†’\n   177â†’**Fix (Option A):**\n   178â†’\n   179â†’```typescript\n   180â†’const maxPositionalBoost =\n   181â†’  hasPipePreamble && isAllCaps(firstCandidate.text) ? 0.22 : 0.15;\n   182â†’```\n   183â†’\n   184â†’**Impact:** Fixes Pattern E. The combined positional boost (+0.22 cap) plus any raw embedding signal should clear the threshold.\n   185â†’\n   186â†’**Risk:** Low. The cap only applies when ALL conditions are met: (1) all preceding lines are filtered, (2) preceding lines include pipe-separated metadata, (3) the candidate is ALL_CAPS. This is a very specific pattern that is nearly always a recipe title.\n   187â†’\n   188â†’---\n   189â†’\n   190â†’## Failure â†’ Fix Mapping\n   191â†’\n   192â†’| Pattern | Cases | Root cause | Fix | Expected outcome |\n   193â†’|---------|-------|-----------|-----|-----------------|\n   194â†’| A: OCR â†’ empty | 2 | `(` merge destroys title | Change 1 | âœ… Title extracted |\n   195â†’| B: OCR â†’ body sentence | 3 | `(` merge destroys title + body line survives | Change 1 | âœ… Title extracted (body already blocked by iter 30 fixes) |\n   196â†’| C: Partial OCR normalization | 1 | `sole` not in dictionary | Change 2 | âœ… `Sole` correctly repaired |\n   197â†’| D: Erratic case â†’ body sentence | 1 | 2-word Polish instruction passes word-count guard | Change 3 | âœ… Instruction filtered, title wins |\n   198â†’| E: Metadata â†’ empty | 1 | Polish ALL_CAPS too weak for MiniLM | Change 4 | âœ… Positional boost sufficient |\n   199â†’| F: Title absent | 1 | Title not in document | **Not fixable** | â‌Œ Remains a failure |\n   200â†’\n   201â†’**Expected result:** 8 of 9 failures fixed â†’ â‰¤1 failure (Mushroom Risotto) â†’ ~99.1% accuracy.\n   202â†’\n   203â†’---\n   204â†’\n   205â†’## Testing Strategy\n   206â†’\n   207â†’### Unit tests\n   208â†’\n   209â†’1. **Continuation merge preserves standalone:**\n   210â†’   - Input: `[\"TITLE LINE\", \"(annotation text)\", \"lngredients:\"]`\n   211â†’   - Verify that both `TITLE LINE` and `TITLE LINE (annotation text)` appear in the candidate list (or just `TITLE LINE` if the merge fails hard filters)\n   212â†’\n   213â†’2. **Dictionary repair for \"sole\":**\n   214â†’   - `repairOcrWord(\"S01e\")` â†’ `\"Sole\"` (after adding `sole` to dictionary)\n   215â†’\n   216â†’3. **Polish 2-word cooking instruction detection:**\n   217â†’   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj ziemniaki.\")` â†’ `true`\n   218â†’   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Podawaؤ‡ ciepإ‚o.\")` â†’ `true`\n   219â†’   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj\")` â†’ `false` (1 word)\n   220â†’   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Roast Chicken\")` â†’ `false` (English, <4 words)\n   221â†’   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Roast the chicken gently\")` â†’ `true` (English, 4 words)\n   222â†’\n   223â†’### Integration tests (eval loop)\n   224â†’\n   225â†’Run the full evaluation suite against all 111 test files:\n   226â†’- 0 regressions on currently-passing files\n   227â†’- 8 newly-passing files (all except Mushroom Risotto)\n   228â†’- Target: â‰¥99% combined accuracy\n   229â†’\n   230â†’### Regression watchlist\n   231â†’\n   232â†’Changes 1 and 3 have the widest blast radius. Specific cases to verify:\n   233â†’\n   234â†’- **Change 1:** `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE` â€” the continuation merge must still produce the full joined title. The standalone `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` will also be generated; existing prefix-removal logic should handle this correctly.\n   235â†’- **Change 1:** `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` â€” `& Coriander` is a continuation; standalone `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce` should not replace the full form.\n   236â†’- **Change 3:** Polish titles starting with words that look like verbs but aren't â€” e.g., `Smaإ¼ona zielona fasolka` starts with `Smaإ¼ona` (adjective \"fried\"), not `Smaإ¼` (imperative \"fry\"). The regex `^sma[zإ¼]\\b` would NOT match `Smaإ¼ona` because `\\b` is after `إ¼`/`z` and before `o` â€” both word chars. âœ“ Safe.\n   237â†’\n   238â†’---\n   239â†’\n   240â†’## Performance Considerations\n   241â†’\n   242â†’All changes are O(1) per candidate:\n   243â†’- Change 1: One extra `push()` per merged line (at most ~5 lines total)\n   244â†’- Change 2: One dictionary entry addition\n   245â†’- Change 3: One regex test moved before the word-count guard\n   246â†’- Change 4: One constant change\n   247â†’\n   248â†’No additional embedding calls. No new async operations. Total impact: negligible (<1ms).\n   249â†’\n   250â†’---\n   251â†’\n   252â†’## Implementation Order\n   253â†’\n   254â†’1. **Change 1** (continuation merge) â€” highest impact, fixes 6/9 failures\n   255â†’2. **Change 3** (Polish cooking instruction threshold) â€” fixes 1 failure, verify no regressions\n   256â†’3. **Change 2** (food dictionary) â€” trivial, fixes 1 failure\n   257â†’4. **Change 4** (positional cap) â€” may not be needed if Change 1 indirectly helps. Implement and verify.\n   258â†’\n   259â†’---\n   260â†’\n   261â†’## Open Questions\n   262â†’\n   263â†’1. **Change 4 necessity:** After Change 1, the `(OCR CORRUPTION...)` annotation line won't be merged with the title anymore. But for the Ogأ³rkowa Zupa case, there's no annotation â€” the issue is purely the pipe-metadata + weak Polish embedding. So Change 4 is still needed independently. However, we should verify the actual raw embedding score for `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` to calibrate the cap correctly.\n   264â†’\n   265â†’2. **Test generator annotations:** The `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` lines in generated test files are synthetic artifacts. Should the test generator be updated to remove them? They serve a documentation purpose but they've now been shown to interact badly with the extraction pipeline. For now, fixing the extractor (Change 1) is the right approach â€” the extractor should be robust to any parenthetical content near the title.\n   266â†’\n   267â†’3. **Broader `(` merge safety:** Beyond `(OCR ...)`, any parenthetical text immediately after a title could trigger the merge. Real OCR output might include page references like `(serves 4)` or `(continued)` after a title. Change 1 handles this by preserving the standalone, so the merged form's failure doesn't destroy the original candidate.\n   268â†’\n   269â†’---\n   270â†’\n   271â†’## References\n   272â†’\n   273â†’- Iteration 29 improvement plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/29-e7e3098/improvement-plan.md`\n   274â†’- Architecture doc: `tools/title-loop/docs/architecture.md`\n   275â†’- Continuation merge introduced: iteration 16 (to fix fragmented titles)\n   276â†’- Positional cap introduced: iteration 26 (+0.15), raised iter 30 (+0.18 for pipe+ALL_CAPS)\n   277â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ac2d9e1b-dbea-4db9-a94b-203c0145980c","uuid":"8eb15468-f954-4516-b38d-b76b8438d7bc","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/30-a2f9b6c/improvement-plan.md","content":"# Iteration 30 â†’ 31 Improvement Plan\n\n**Status:** Draft\n**Date:** 2026-03-17\n**Baseline:** 91.9% combined accuracy (9 failures, all generated; 0 real failures)\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nIteration 30 implemented all 6 changes from the iter 29 plan (OCR repair, garbled detection, Polish verbs, positional bonus). Yet the same 9 failures persist. The iter 29 analysis was correct about downstream symptoms but missed the true root cause for 6 of 9 failures.\n\n**The primary root cause is the continuation-line merge in `buildCandidates`** (lines 646â€“658). The merge treats `(` as a continuation character, so any parenthetical annotation line immediately following the title gets merged with it. The merged result fails the â‰¥8-word or â‰¥80-char hard filter, and the original single-line title is never generated as a candidate. All iter 29 fixes (OCR repair, cooking verb detection) were correct but never had a chance to fire because the title was destroyed before candidate generation.\n\n---\n\n## Root Cause Deep Dive\n\n### The continuation merge bug (6/9 failures)\n\n`buildCandidates` pre-merges continuation lines (lines 646â€“658):\n\n```typescript\nif (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n  mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n  i++;  // â†گ skips nextText AND loses the original line.text as a standalone\n  continue;\n}\n```\n\nThe regex `^[/&+:(]` is designed for real continuations like `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS` + `/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`. But it also matches the synthetic `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` annotation lines that the test generator places on line 3 of each generated file.\n\n**Trace for \"Braised Cod with White Wine\":**\n\n1. Non-empty lines: `[0] Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`, `[1] (OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation)`, `[2] lngredients:`\n2. Continuation merge: line `[1]` starts with `(` â†’ merged with `[0]`\n3. Merged text: `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne (OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation)` (11 words)\n4. `repairOcrText` â†’ `Braised Cod with White Wine (OCR CORRUPTION: digit for letter, hyphenation)`\n5. `passesHardFilters`: fails `words.length >= 8` check â†’ rejected\n6. The original standalone `Braised Cod with White Wine` was never generated\n\n**Same mechanism for:** Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip, Droإ¼dإ¼e Sernik, Piernik z إڑliwkami, إ»urek Krakowski (5 more cases, all have `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` on line 3).\n\n### Remaining root causes (3/9 failures)\n\n| Pattern | Case | Root cause |\n|---------|------|-----------|\n| C: Partial OCR normalization | Sole with Brown Butter and Capers | `sole` not in food dictionary; blind repair maps `01â†’oi` (i-variant) instead of `0â†’o, 1â†’l` (l-variant). No annotation merge issue â€” file has no `(OCR ...)` line. |\n| D: Erratic casing + `آ،` | Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leإ›nymi | No merge issue (line 2 is regular text). The erratic-casing normalization + blind `آ،â†’i` repair should produce `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leإ›nymi` as a candidate. Issue is downstream: the cooking instruction `Ugotuj ziemniaky.` (2 words) passes the `looksLikeCookingInstruction` word-count guard (requires â‰¥4) and outscores the title. |\n| E: Metadata â†’ empty | Ogأ³rkowa Zupa | Pipe-separated metadata filtered correctly, `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` should be candidate. MiniLM gives weak score for Polish ALL_CAPS; positional bonus cap may be too low. |\n| F: Title absent | Mushroom Risotto | Title doesn't appear in document. Not fixable without external context. |\n\n---\n\n## Goals\n\n- Fix the 6 continuation-merge failures (Patterns A, B: all files with `(OCR ...)` annotations)\n- Fix Pattern C (Sole: dictionary gap)\n- Fix Pattern D (Kopytka: short cooking instruction not caught)\n- Fix Pattern E (Ogأ³rkowa Zupa: Polish ALL_CAPS weak embedding)\n- Maintain 100% accuracy on real files\n- No regressions on currently-passing generated files\n- Keep total extraction time under 10 seconds on device\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Fix Pattern F (Mushroom Risotto: title absent from document) â€” requires page-level context\n- Change the embedding model â€” MiniLM works well for 102+ passing cases\n- Restructure the full candidate generation pipeline â€” only the merge logic needs fixing\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Changes\n\n### Change 1: Preserve standalone candidate when continuation-merging\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, lines 646â€“658\n\n**Problem:** The continuation merge replaces the original line with the merged form and skips ahead. The original short form is never added to `mergedLines`, so it can never become a candidate.\n\n**Fix:** Always emit the original line as well as the merged form. The downstream `seen` set in the candidate loop (line 661) will deduplicate if both forms produce the same normalized text.\n\n```typescript\nfor (let i = 0; i < capsCoalesced.length; i++) {\n  const line = capsCoalesced[i];\n  mergedLines.push(line);  // â†گ always keep the original\n  if (i + 1 < capsCoalesced.length) {\n    const nextText = capsCoalesced[i + 1].text;\n    if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n      mergedLines.push({ text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`, index: line.index });\n      i++;\n      continue;\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Why this is safe:** The `seen` set deduplicates by normalized text. If both the standalone and the merge produce passing candidates, both enter the pool â€” the dedup and scoring logic downstream picks the better one. If the merge fails hard filters (as in the annotation case), only the standalone survives. If the standalone fails (rare â€” means the line is truly garbled), the merge might still pass. This is strictly more capable than the current approach.\n\n**Risk assessment:** Low. The continuation merge was designed for cases like `TITLE / SUBTITLE` where the `/` line is meaningless on its own. In those cases, the standalone `TITLE` will still be generated AND the merge `TITLE / SUBTITLE` will also be generated. The existing dedup, prefix-removal, and multi-title logic handles this correctly â€” the test for `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE` already has the prefix-removal step that eliminates the standalone when the merge is better.\n\n**Impact:** Directly fixes 6 of 9 failures. After this change, `Braised Cod with White Wine` enters the candidate pool as a standalone, gets dictionary-repaired, scores well against the title embedding, and is selected.\n\n**Cross-iteration note:** This is NOT the same as \"removing the continuation merge\" â€” the merge still runs and produces joined candidates. It's adding the standalone alongside it. The merge was introduced in iter 16 to fix fragmented titles; this change preserves that behavior while preventing annotation-merge destruction.\n\n---\n\n### Change 2: Add \"sole\" and related fish names to the food dictionary\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n\n**Problem:** `S01e with Brown Butter and Capers` â€” `sole` is not in the food dictionary, so dictionary-guided repair can't resolve the ambiguity. The blind repair produces `Soie` (0â†’o, 1â†’i) instead of `Sole` (0â†’o, 1â†’l).\n\n**Fix:** Add missing common fish/food names to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`:\n\n```typescript\n\"sole\",     // flatfish â€” needed for \"S01e\" OCR repair\n\"soie\",     // NOT a food word â€” do not add (French for silk)\n```\n\nWith `sole` in the dictionary, `repairOcrWord(\"S01e\")` generates candidates including `sole` (0â†’o, 1â†’l), finds it in the dictionary, and returns `Sole`.\n\n**Impact:** Directly fixes Pattern C. The title becomes `Sole with Brown Butter and Capers` instead of `Soie with Brown Butter and Capers`.\n\n**Risk:** None. `sole` is unambiguously a food item in the context of recipe text.\n\n---\n\n### Change 3: Lower word-count threshold for cooking instruction detection\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `looksLikeCookingInstruction` (line 364)\n\n**Problem:** `Ugotuj ziemniaky.` (2 words) passes through the cooking instruction filter because the guard requires `words.length >= 4`. This 2-word cooking instruction then enters the candidate pool and outscores the title `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leإ›nymi`.\n\nThe `>= 4` threshold was originally set to prevent short recipe titles like `Roast Chicken` or `Grilled Salmon` from being falsely classified as cooking instructions. But it's too permissive â€” `Ugotuj ziemniaky.` and `Upiecz chleb.` are clearly instructions, not titles.\n\n**Fix:** Split the word-count guard by language:\n\n```typescript\nfunction looksLikeCookingInstruction(text: string): boolean {\n  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n  // English cooking instructions are typically â‰¥4 words (\"Roast the chicken until...\")\n  // but short English imperatives can also be recipe titles (\"Roast Chicken\", \"Grilled Salmon\").\n  // Polish cooking instructions are commonly 2-3 words (\"Ugotuj ziemniaki.\", \"Upiecz chleb.\")\n  // and are unambiguous because Polish recipe titles don't start with imperative verbs.\n  if (POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) {\n    return words.length >= 2;  // Polish: 2+ words is enough\n  }\n  if (words.length < 4) return false;  // English: keep existing 4-word threshold\n  if (COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\n  return false;\n}\n```\n\n**Why this is safe for Polish but not English:**\n- Polish recipe titles never start with bare imperative verbs. The title is always a noun phrase: `Piernik z إڑliwkami`, `Kopytka z Pieczarkami`, `إ»urek Krakowski`. The cooking section uses imperatives: `Ugotuj`, `Podawaj`, `Dodaj`.\n- English recipe titles CAN start with the same words as cooking instructions: `Roast Chicken` (title) vs `Roast the chicken` (instruction). The 4-word guard protects these.\n\n**Impact:** Fixes Pattern D. `Ugotuj ziemniaky.` is now caught as a cooking instruction, never enters the candidate pool. The title `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leإ›nymi` (after erratic-casing normalization and `آ،â†’i` repair) wins.\n\n**Risk:** Low. Polish imperative verbs at the start of a line are unambiguously instructions. No Polish recipe title in the test suite or in common cookbook conventions starts with an imperative verb.\n\n---\n\n### Change 4: Strengthen Polish ALL_CAPS positional signal for pipe-metadata preamble\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, positional bonus logic (lines ~1230â€“1246)\n\n**Problem:** `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` appears after a pipe-separated metadata line. The candidate enters the pool and gets the pipe-preamble positional bonus (+0.12), the direct-successor bonus (+0.10), but the combined boost is capped at 0.18 (the pipe+ALL_CAPS special cap from iter 30). MiniLM gives a weak raw embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS text (likely near 0 or slightly negative), so even with +0.18 boost, the candidate may fall below the threshold.\n\n**Investigation:** The iter 29 plan already raised the cap from 0.15 to 0.18 for pipe+ALL_CAPS. If 0.18 is still insufficient, there are two options:\n\n**Option A (preferred): Raise the cap to 0.22 for pipe+ALL_CAPS.** The pipe-metadata + ALL_CAPS pattern is a near-certain title indicator in Polish cookbooks. The extra 0.04 headroom accounts for MiniLM's English bias.\n\n**Option B: Lower the rawScore floor for pipe+ALL_CAPS candidates.** Currently the fallback path requires `rawScore > -0.05` for early-position candidates. For pipe+ALL_CAPS, this could be relaxed to `-0.10`. But this is riskier â€” it allows weaker candidates through.\n\n**Fix (Option A):**\n\n```typescript\nconst maxPositionalBoost =\n  hasPipePreamble && isAllCaps(firstCandidate.text) ? 0.22 : 0.15;\n```\n\n**Impact:** Fixes Pattern E. The combined positional boost (+0.22 cap) plus any raw embedding signal should clear the threshold.\n\n**Risk:** Low. The cap only applies when ALL conditions are met: (1) all preceding lines are filtered, (2) preceding lines include pipe-separated metadata, (3) the candidate is ALL_CAPS. This is a very specific pattern that is nearly always a recipe title.\n\n---\n\n## Failure â†’ Fix Mapping\n\n| Pattern | Cases | Root cause | Fix | Expected outcome |\n|---------|-------|-----------|-----|-----------------|\n| A: OCR â†’ empty | 2 | `(` merge destroys title | Change 1 | âœ… Title extracted |\n| B: OCR â†’ body sentence | 3 | `(` merge destroys title + body line survives | Change 1 | âœ… Title extracted (body already blocked by iter 30 fixes) |\n| C: Partial OCR normalization | 1 | `sole` not in dictionary | Change 2 | âœ… `Sole` correctly repaired |\n| D: Erratic case â†’ body sentence | 1 | 2-word Polish instruction passes word-count guard | Change 3 | âœ… Instruction filtered, title wins |\n| E: Metadata â†’ empty | 1 | Polish ALL_CAPS too weak for MiniLM | Change 4 | âœ… Positional boost sufficient |\n| F: Title absent | 1 | Title not in document | **Not fixable** | â‌Œ Remains a failure |\n\n**Expected result:** 8 of 9 failures fixed â†’ â‰¤1 failure (Mushroom Risotto) â†’ ~99.1% accuracy.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit tests\n\n1. **Continuation merge preserves standalone:**\n   - Input: `[\"TITLE LINE\", \"(annotation text)\", \"lngredients:\"]`\n   - Verify that both `TITLE LINE` and `TITLE LINE (annotation text)` appear in the candidate list (or just `TITLE LINE` if the merge fails hard filters)\n\n2. **Dictionary repair for \"sole\":**\n   - `repairOcrWord(\"S01e\")` â†’ `\"Sole\"` (after adding `sole` to dictionary)\n\n3. **Polish 2-word cooking instruction detection:**\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj ziemniaki.\")` â†’ `true`\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Podawaؤ‡ ciepإ‚o.\")` â†’ `true`\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj\")` â†’ `false` (1 word)\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Roast Chicken\")` â†’ `false` (English, <4 words)\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Roast the chicken gently\")` â†’ `true` (English, 4 words)\n\n### Integration tests (eval loop)\n\nRun the full evaluation suite against all 111 test files:\n- 0 regressions on currently-passing files\n- 8 newly-passing files (all except Mushroom Risotto)\n- Target: â‰¥99% combined accuracy\n\n### Regression watchlist\n\nChanges 1 and 3 have the widest blast radius. Specific cases to verify:\n\n- **Change 1:** `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE` â€” the continuation merge must still produce the full joined title. The standalone `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` will also be generated; existing prefix-removal logic should handle this correctly.\n- **Change 1:** `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` â€” `& Coriander` is a continuation; standalone `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce` should not replace the full form.\n- **Change 3:** Polish titles starting with words that look like verbs but aren't â€” e.g., `Smaإ¼ona zielona fasolka` starts with `Smaإ¼ona` (adjective \"fried\"), not `Smaإ¼` (imperative \"fry\"). The regex `^sma[zإ¼]\\b` would NOT match `Smaإ¼ona` because `\\b` is after `إ¼`/`z` and before `o` â€” both word chars. âœ“ Safe.\n\n---\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\nAll changes are O(1) per candidate:\n- Change 1: One extra `push()` per merged line (at most ~5 lines total)\n- Change 2: One dictionary entry addition\n- Change 3: One regex test moved before the word-count guard\n- Change 4: One constant change\n\nNo additional embedding calls. No new async operations. Total impact: negligible (<1ms).\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Order\n\n1. **Change 1** (continuation merge) â€” highest impact, fixes 6/9 failures\n2. **Change 3** (Polish cooking instruction threshold) â€” fixes 1 failure, verify no regressions\n3. **Change 2** (food dictionary) â€” trivial, fixes 1 failure\n4. **Change 4** (positional cap) â€” may not be needed if Change 1 indirectly helps. Implement and verify.\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. **Change 4 necessity:** After Change 1, the `(OCR CORRUPTION...)` annotation line won't be merged with the title anymore. But for the Ogأ³rkowa Zupa case, there's no annotation â€” the issue is purely the pipe-metadata + weak Polish embedding. So Change 4 is still needed independently. However, we should verify the actual raw embedding score for `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` to calibrate the cap correctly.\n\n2. **Test generator annotations:** The `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` lines in generated test files are synthetic artifacts. Should the test generator be updated to remove them? They serve a documentation purpose but they've now been shown to interact badly with the extraction pipeline. For now, fixing the extractor (Change 1) is the right approach â€” the extractor should be robust to any parenthetical content near the title.\n\n3. **Broader `(` merge safety:** Beyond `(OCR ...)`, any parenthetical text immediately after a title could trigger the merge. Real OCR output might include page references like `(serves 4)` or `(continued)` after a title. Change 1 handles this by preserving the standalone, so the merged form's failure doesn't destroy the original candidate.\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Iteration 29 improvement plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/29-e7e3098/improvement-plan.md`\n- Architecture doc: `tools/title-loop/docs/architecture.md`\n- Continuation merge introduced: iteration 16 (to fix fragmented titles)\n- Positional cap introduced: iteration 26 (+0.15), raised iter 30 (+0.18 for pipe+ALL_CAPS)\n","numLines":277,"startLine":1,"totalLines":277}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Pd6cVzYhCXXi6QCQyZnUNh","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Iteration 30 â€” Failure Analysis\n     2â†’\n     3â†’All 9 failures are generated files; 0 real files failed.\n     4â†’\n     5â†’---\n     6â†’\n     7â†’## Pattern A: OCR digit-for-letter corruption â†’ empty result (2 cases)\n     8â†’\n     9â†’**Failures:** Braised Cod with White Wine, Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip\n    10â†’\n    11â†’The title line contains digits substituted for letters (`Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`, `Roasted Beet and Walnut D1p`). The extractor rejects the corrupted line and returns nothing rather than attempting normalization or falling back to a later occurrence.\n    12â†’\n    13â†’Expected a normalized title; got empty string.\n    14â†’\n    15â†’---\n    16â†’\n    17â†’## Pattern B: OCR digit-for-letter corruption â†’ body sentence extracted (3 cases)\n    18â†’\n    19â†’**Failures:** Droإ¼dإ¼e Sernik, Piernik z إڑliwkami, إ»urek Krakowski\n    20â†’\n    21â†’Similar digit-for-letter corruption on the title line (`Sern1k`, `P1ern1k`, plus garbage tokens). The extractor rejects the title line but then incorrectly falls back to a sentence from the recipe body (e.g., \"Podawaؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.\", \"Traditional Easter soup of Greater Poland.\").\n    22â†’\n    23â†’Expected the corrupted title (normalized); got an unrelated body sentence.\n    24â†’\n    25â†’---\n    26â†’\n    27â†’## Pattern C: OCR corruption partially normalized, incorrectly (1 case)\n    28â†’\n    29â†’**Failure:** Sole with Brown Butter and Capers\n    30â†’\n    31â†’Title line `S01e with Brown Butter and Capers` â€” the extractor attempted to normalize `S01e` but produced `Soie` instead of `Sole`. The digit `0` was converted to `o` but `1` became `i`, yielding a plausible-looking but wrong word.\n    32â†’\n    33â†’Expected \"Sole\"; got \"Soie\". The normalization heuristic (digitâ†’letter mapping) is imprecise for this case.\n    34â†’\n    35â†’---\n    36â†’\n    37â†’## Pattern D: Mixed/unusual casing and special characters â†’ body sentence (1 case)\n    38â†’\n    39â†’**Failure:** Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leإ›nymi\n    40â†’\n    41â†’Title line `KoPyTka z Pآ،eczarkami Leإ›nymi` has erratic capitalization and a dotless-i (`آ،`) character. The extractor likely rejected it (or failed to score it as a title) and fell back to a body sentence (\"Ugotuj ziemniaky.\").\n    42â†’\n    43â†’Expected the title; got a cooking instruction sentence.\n    44â†’\n    45â†’---\n    46â†’\n    47â†’## Pattern E: Metadata/tags line precedes ALL-CAPS title â†’ empty result (1 case)\n    48â†’\n    49â†’**Failure:** Ogأ³rkowa Zupa\n    50â†’\n    51â†’The document opens with a metadata line (`Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSأ“B | PRZYGOTOWANIE 15 MIN | GOTOWANIE 20 MIN`) followed by the title in ALL CAPS (`OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA`). The extractor apparently gets confused by the metadata line or doesn't recognize the ALL-CAPS form as a title, returning empty.\n    52â†’\n    53â†’Expected \"Ogأ³rkowa Zupa\"; got empty string.\n    54â†’\n    55â†’---\n    56â†’\n    57â†’## Pattern F: Title absent from document start â†’ wrong title extracted (1 case)\n    58â†’\n    59â†’**Failure:** Mushroom Risotto\n    60â†’\n    61â†’The document begins mid-recipe with body prose (describing risotto technique), and the title `Mushroom Risotto` never appears at the top. A different recipe title (`CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA`) appears later in the document and was extracted instead.\n    62â†’\n    63â†’Expected \"Mushroom Risotto\"; got \"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA + CARPACCIO WITH CITRUS DRESSING\". The extractor correctly found a recipe title in the text â€” just not the right one, because the true title was never present at the expected position.\n    64â†’\n    65â†’---\n    66â†’\n    67â†’## Summary by affected file type\n    68â†’\n    69â†’All 9 failures are **generated files only**. No real files failed this iteration.\n    70â†’\n    71â†’The dominant issue is OCR corruption on the first line (Patterns A, B, C, D â€” 7/9 cases): the extractor is not robust to digit-for-letter substitutions and unusual casing on the title line. Secondary issues are metadata headers before the title (Pattern E) and documents where the true title is simply absent from the beginning (Pattern F).\n    72â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ac2d9e1b-dbea-4db9-a94b-203c0145980c","uuid":"627accb9-2239-4197-82ee-749474b10cfc","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/30-a2f9b6c/feedback.md","content":"# Iteration 30 â€” Failure Analysis\n\nAll 9 failures are generated files; 0 real files failed.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern A: OCR digit-for-letter corruption â†’ empty result (2 cases)\n\n**Failures:** Braised Cod with White Wine, Roasted Beet and Walnut Dip\n\nThe title line contains digits substituted for letters (`Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`, `Roasted Beet and Walnut D1p`). The extractor rejects the corrupted line and returns nothing rather than attempting normalization or falling back to a later occurrence.\n\nExpected a normalized title; got empty string.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern B: OCR digit-for-letter corruption â†’ body sentence extracted (3 cases)\n\n**Failures:** Droإ¼dإ¼e Sernik, Piernik z إڑliwkami, إ»urek Krakowski\n\nSimilar digit-for-letter corruption on the title line (`Sern1k`, `P1ern1k`, plus garbage tokens). The extractor rejects the title line but then incorrectly falls back to a sentence from the recipe body (e.g., \"Podawaؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.\", \"Traditional Easter soup of Greater Poland.\").\n\nExpected the corrupted title (normalized); got an unrelated body sentence.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern C: OCR corruption partially normalized, incorrectly (1 case)\n\n**Failure:** Sole with Brown Butter and Capers\n\nTitle line `S01e with Brown Butter and Capers` â€” the extractor attempted to normalize `S01e` but produced `Soie` instead of `Sole`. The digit `0` was converted to `o` but `1` became `i`, yielding a plausible-looking but wrong word.\n\nExpected \"Sole\"; got \"Soie\". The normalization heuristic (digitâ†’letter mapping) is imprecise for this case.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern D: Mixed/unusual casing and special characters â†’ body sentence (1 case)\n\n**Failure:** Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leإ›nymi\n\nTitle line `KoPyTka z Pآ،eczarkami Leإ›nymi` has erratic capitalization and a dotless-i (`آ،`) character. The extractor likely rejected it (or failed to score it as a title) and fell back to a body sentence (\"Ugotuj ziemniaky.\").\n\nExpected the title; got a cooking instruction sentence.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern E: Metadata/tags line precedes ALL-CAPS title â†’ empty result (1 case)\n\n**Failure:** Ogأ³rkowa Zupa\n\nThe document opens with a metadata line (`Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSأ“B | PRZYGOTOWANIE 15 MIN | GOTOWANIE 20 MIN`) followed by the title in ALL CAPS (`OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA`). The extractor apparently gets confused by the metadata line or doesn't recognize the ALL-CAPS form as a title, returning empty.\n\nExpected \"Ogأ³rkowa Zupa\"; got empty string.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern F: Title absent from document start â†’ wrong title extracted (1 case)\n\n**Failure:** Mushroom Risotto\n\nThe document begins mid-recipe with body prose (describing risotto technique), and the title `Mushroom Risotto` never appears at the top. A different recipe title (`CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA`) appears later in the document and was extracted instead.\n\nExpected \"Mushroom Risotto\"; got \"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA + CARPACCIO WITH CITRUS DRESSING\". The extractor correctly found a recipe title in the text â€” just not the right one, because the true title was never present at the expected position.\n\n---\n\n## Summary by affected file type\n\nAll 9 failures are **generated files only**. No real files failed this iteration.\n\nThe dominant issue is OCR corruption on the first line (Patterns A, B, C, D â€” 7/9 cases): the extractor is not robust to digit-for-letter substitutions and unusual casing on the title line. Secondary issues are metadata headers before the title (Pattern E) and documents where the true title is simply absent from the beginning (Pattern F).\n","numLines":72,"startLine":1,"totalLines":72}}}
