{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0115h9khJzdrbBgKUsbFR5Sc","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Iteration 26 â†’ 27 Improvement Plan\n     2â†’\n     3â†’## Title\n     4â†’\n     5â†’Fix generated-file title extraction: OCR repair gaps, section-label merge blocking, and spillover handling\n     6â†’\n     7â†’## Status\n     8â†’\n     9â†’Draft\n    10â†’\n    11â†’## Authors\n    12â†’\n    13â†’Claude â€” 2026-03-17\n    14â†’\n    15â†’## Overview\n    16â†’\n    17â†’Iteration 26 has 0 real-file failures and 16 generated-file failures across 6 patterns.\n    18â†’Real accuracy is 100% (11/11). Combined accuracy is 85.6%.\n    19â†’\n    20â†’The failures share two root causes:\n    21â†’\n    22â†’1. **OCR repair has blind spots** â€” the food dictionary lacks common English words\n    23â†’   (`with`, `the`, `and`, `dip`, `pie`), so `repairOcrWord` can't fix them. Partially-\n    24â†’   repaired titles like `Braised Cod w1th White Wine` score poorly on embeddings and\n    25â†’   get skipped.\n    26â†’\n    27â†’2. **Structural heuristics are too rigid** â€” section labels block multi-line title\n    28â†’   merges even when the label is clearly a title continuation; spillover markers don't\n    29â†’   trigger a wider scan; and mid-recipe pages aren't reliably detected when body text\n    30â†’   precedes ingredients.\n    31â†’\n    32â†’The fix addresses both causes with targeted changes: expand the OCR repair dictionary,\n    33â†’relax section-label merge blocking for title continuations, and improve spillover/\n    34â†’mid-recipe detection. The pipeline architecture is unchanged.\n    35â†’\n    36â†’## Background / Problem Statement\n    37â†’\n    38â†’### Failure breakdown\n    39â†’\n    40â†’| Pattern | Count | Returns | Root cause |\n    41â†’|---------|-------|---------|------------|\n    42â†’| A. Corrupted spillover â€” title absent | 5 | empty | `findBurstEnd` skips spillover marker but doesn't scan far enough for the title |\n    43â†’| B. Heavy digit corruption â€” title rejected | 2 | empty | `repairOcrText` can't fix `w1th`, `D1p` (not in food dictionary) â†’ corrupted title fails embedding scoring |\n    44â†’| C. Partial corruption â€” wrong body line | 3 | wrong | Same as B â€” partially-repaired title scores lower than a body text line |\n    45â†’| D. Section header before title | 3 | wrong/empty | First-after-preamble bonus isn't firing for all cases; pipe-delimited metadata followed by title not handled |\n    46â†’| E. Multi-line title truncated | 1 | partial | `VEGETABLES` is in `SECTION_LABELS`, so caps-coalescing refuses to merge it with preceding `LEMON HERB ROASTED` |\n    47â†’| F. Mid-recipe page start | 2 | wrong | `isTitleAbsentPage` checks first 3 lines for ingredients/instructions, but body text (prose) isn't detected |\n    48â†’\n    49â†’### What works well (do not change)\n    50â†’\n    51â†’- Pipeline architecture: candidate generation â†’ hard filters â†’ embedding scoring â†’ multi-title assembly\n    52â†’- Dictionary-guided OCR repair mechanism (just needs a wider dictionary)\n    53â†’- Vocabulary corroboration for multi-title assembly (iteration 25 fix)\n    54â†’- Compound title dedup protection\n    55â†’- Bilingual detection (both ALL_CAPS and mixed-case variants)\n    56â†’- Real file accuracy: 100%\n    57â†’- Shorter-wins dedup rule (DO NOT CHANGE â€” see architecture.md warning)\n    58â†’\n    59â†’## Goals\n    60â†’\n    61â†’- Fix all 16 generated-file failures without regressing real files\n    62â†’- Keep changes minimal and localized within the existing pipeline stages\n    63â†’\n    64â†’## Non-Goals\n    65â†’\n    66â†’- Replacing the embedding model or scoring architecture\n    67â†’- Reworking the overall pipeline structure\n    68â†’- Adding new generated test files\n    69â†’- Changing the dedup logic\n    70â†’\n    71â†’---\n    72â†’\n    73â†’## Detailed Design\n    74â†’\n    75â†’### Fix 1: Expand OCR repair dictionary with common English words (Patterns B, C)\n    76â†’\n    77â†’**Root cause detail:** `repairOcrWord` only matches against `FOOD_DICTIONARY`. Common\n    78â†’English words that appear in recipe titles â€” prepositions (`with`, `the`, `for`),\n    79â†’adjectives (`old`, `new`, `hot`), and short food terms (`dip`, `pie`, `jam`, `bun`) â€”\n    80â†’are missing. When these words contain OCR digits, repair fails and the candidate enters\n    81â†’embedding scoring with residual corruption.\n    82â†’\n    83â†’Tracing Pattern B failure `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`:\n    84â†’- `Bra1sed` â†’ `braised` âœ“ (in dictionary)\n    85â†’- `Cod` â†’ no digits, passes through âœ“\n    86â†’- `w1th` â†’ tries `with` (1â†’i) â†’ NOT in dictionary â†’ stays `w1th` âœ—\n    87â†’- `Wh1te` â†’ `white` âœ“\n    88â†’- `W1ne` â†’ `wine` âœ“\n    89â†’\n    90â†’Result after repair: `Braised Cod w1th White Wine` â€” the residual `w1th` degrades\n    91â†’embedding quality enough to push the title below threshold.\n    92â†’\n    93â†’**Fix:** Add a `COMMON_TITLE_WORDS` set to `food-dictionary.ts` containing ~50 words\n    94â†’that commonly appear in recipe titles but aren't food-specific:\n    95â†’\n    96â†’```typescript\n    97â†’// Common English words that appear in recipe titles (for OCR repair)\n    98â†’const COMMON_TITLE_WORDS: Set<string> = new Set([\n    99â†’  // Prepositions & conjunctions\n   100â†’  \"with\", \"from\", \"over\", \"under\",\n   101â†’  // Adjectives\n   102â†’  \"classic\", \"simple\", \"quick\", \"easy\", \"light\",\n   103â†’  \"thick\", \"thin\", \"crispy\", \"creamy\", \"spicy\",\n   104â†’  // Short food terms missing from main dictionary\n   105â†’  \"dip\", \"pie\", \"bun\", \"buns\", \"roll\", \"rolls\",\n   106â†’  \"jam\", \"jelly\", \"tart\", \"cake\", \"loaf\",\n   107â†’  \"soup\", \"stew\", \"hash\", \"bowl\", \"wrap\",\n   108â†’  // Polish common title words\n   109â†’  \"pieczony\", \"pieczone\", \"smaإ¼ony\", \"smaإ¼one\",\n   110â†’  \"gotowany\", \"gotowane\", \"duszone\", \"duszony\",\n   111â†’  \"domowy\", \"domowe\", \"tradycyjny\", \"tradycyjne\",\n   112â†’]);\n   113â†’```\n   114â†’\n   115â†’Merge this into `FOOD_DICTIONARY` (or check both sets in `repairOcrWord`). The\n   116â†’simpler approach is to add these words directly to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`.\n   117â†’\n   118â†’**Expected impact:** Fixes B (2) and C (3) = 5 failures. After full repair,\n   119â†’`Braised Cod with White Wine` scores correctly on embeddings and wins over body text.\n   120â†’\n   121â†’### Fix 2: Allow section-label words in multi-line title merges (Pattern E)\n   122â†’\n   123â†’**Root cause detail:** In the caps-coalescing loop (line ~510-548), the condition\n   124â†’`!isSectionLabel(next.text)` prevents `VEGETABLES` from merging with the preceding\n   125â†’`LEMON HERB ROASTED`. But `LEMON HERB ROASTED` is clearly an incomplete title\n   126â†’fragment (3 words, ends mid-phrase). The section-label check is correct in general\n   127â†’(prevent merging `SKإپADNIKI` into a title), but too aggressive for single words\n   128â†’that complete an obviously truncated preceding line.\n   129â†’\n   130â†’**Cross-iteration tension:** Iterations 18 and 22 deliberately added `\"vegetables\"`\n   131â†’(and other food-category words) to `SECTION_LABELS` to prevent standalone `VEGETABLES`\n   132â†’from being selected as a title. This fix relaxes that protection for merges while\n   133â†’preserving it for standalone candidates. The `\"placki\"` precedent from iteration 22\n   134â†’(removed from `SECTION_LABELS` entirely because it starts recipe titles) shows the\n   135â†’project already acknowledges that category words can legitimately appear in titles.\n   136â†’\n   137â†’**Fix:** Relax the section-label merge block when the **preceding merged text** is\n   138â†’short (â‰¤ 4 words) and the next line is a single word. The heuristic: a short ALL_CAPS\n   139â†’fragment followed by a single ALL_CAPS word that happens to be a section label is more\n   140â†’likely a fragmented title than a title followed by a section header.\n   141â†’\n   142â†’```typescript\n   143â†’// In caps-coalescing loop, replace:\n   144â†’//   !isSectionLabel(next.text)\n   145â†’// with:\n   146â†’//   !isSectionLabel(next.text) ||\n   147â†’//   (wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4)\n   148â†’```\n   149â†’\n   150â†’Additionally, check that the repaired form of the section label doesn't match either.\n   151â†’The existing code already checks `!isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text))` â€” extend\n   152â†’the relaxation to also apply when this check would have blocked the merge.\n   153â†’\n   154â†’**Safety:** Only fires for single-word section labels following short ALL_CAPS\n   155â†’fragments. Multi-word section labels (`SPOSOB WYKONANIA`) are unaffected. And\n   156â†’`SKإپADNIKI` following a complete 5+ word title would NOT merge (the word count\n   157â†’guard prevents it). Standalone `VEGETABLES` as a candidate (without a preceding\n   158â†’short fragment) is still blocked by SECTION_LABELS â€” this relaxation only applies\n   159â†’to the merge path, not the standalone candidate filter.\n   160â†’\n   161â†’**Expected impact:** Fixes E (1) = 1 failure. `LEMON HERB ROASTED` + `VEGETABLES`\n   162â†’â†’ `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES`.\n   163â†’\n   164â†’### Fix 3: Improve spillover handling in `findBurstEnd` (Pattern A)\n   165â†’\n   166â†’**Root cause detail:** When a file starts with `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]`, the\n   167â†’hard filter in `passesHardFilters` correctly rejects the spillover annotation line.\n   168â†’The `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` regex already includes `SPILLOVER` as a match, so\n   169â†’`findBurstEnd` detects the marker. However, after detecting the marker, `findBurstEnd`\n   170â†’looks for a separator (blank line or `====`) to determine where the preamble ends.\n   171â†’If the spillover content continues as body text without a clear separator,\n   172â†’`findBurstEnd` doesn't advance far enough. The title may be buried at line 10+ or\n   173â†’absent entirely, and the extractor gives up because no candidate emerges near the\n   174â†’(insufficiently advanced) burst end.\n   175â†’\n   176â†’**Note (iteration 25 context):** Iteration 25 analyzed this same pattern and noted\n   177â†’that `findBurstEnd` \"doesn't skip the garbled preamble lines (they're long, not\n   178â†’short), so the proposed `i > 0` guard would never fire.\" The core issue is\n   179â†’skip-distance, not marker detection.\n   180â†’\n   181â†’**Fix:** Two changes:\n   182â†’\n   183â†’1. Improve `findBurstEnd`'s post-marker skip logic. After detecting an overflow\n   184â†’   marker (including `SPILLOVER`), skip ALL subsequent lines until either:\n   185â†’   (a) a gap of â‰¥2 consecutive blank lines,\n   186â†’   (b) a separator line (`====`, `----`), or\n   187â†’   (c) an ALL_CAPS line with â‰¥2 words (structural signal for a new recipe heading).\n   188â†’\n   189â†’   This replaces the current \"look for next blank line\" logic which fails when\n   190â†’   spillover body text continues without separators.\n   191â†’\n   192â†’2. In `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, when `findBurstEnd` was able to skip a spillover\n   193â†’   preamble, relax the position preference â€” don't penalize candidates at position 10+\n   194â†’   just because they're far from line 0. The title position after a spillover can be\n   195â†’   anywhere in the document.\n   196â†’\n   197â†’   Specifically: when `burstEnd > 0` and an overflow marker was detected, set the\n   198â†’   position factor to treat the first post-burst candidate as position 0 for scoring.\n   199â†’   This is already partially handled by the candidate-relative position bonus, but\n   200â†’   `findBurstEnd` needs to actually advance past the spillover content for it to work.\n   201â†’\n   202â†’**Expected impact:** Fixes A (5) = 5 failures for cases where the title exists later\n   203â†’in the document. For cases where the title is truly absent (was on the previous page),\n   204â†’the extractor should return empty â€” which it already does when no candidates survive.\n   205â†’\n   206â†’### Fix 4: Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus for Pattern D cases\n   207â†’\n   208â†’**Root cause detail:** The first-after-preamble bonus (line ~964-977) checks whether\n   209â†’ALL preceding lines were filtered or empty. For the Halibut case, `FISH & SEAFOOD`\n   210â†’is filtered as a section label, so the check should pass. But the bonus is only +0.08.\n   211â†’If the actual title (`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce`) has a weak rawScore against\n   212â†’the title reference embedding (it's a mixed-case description-like string), +0.08 may\n   213â†’not be enough to clear the threshold.\n   214â†’\n   215â†’For Ogأ³rkowa Zupa, the pipe-delimited metadata line is correctly filtered, and\n   216â†’`OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` at position 2 should be an ALL_CAPS structural heading candidate.\n   217â†’The issue may be that `OGأ“RKOWA` contains the OCR-challenging `أ“` which could affect\n   218â†’embedding quality, or that the first-after-preamble check doesn't fire because there's\n   219â†’a non-filtered blank line at position 1.\n   220â†’\n   221â†’**Fix:** Two adjustments:\n   222â†’\n   223â†’1. Make the first-after-preamble check more robust by also treating blank lines as\n   224â†’   \"filtered\" (they already are treated as empty, but ensure the check includes them):\n   225â†’\n   226â†’   ```typescript\n   227â†’   const allPrecedingFiltered = lines\n   228â†’     .slice(0, firstCandidate.position)\n   229â†’     .every((line) => {\n   230â†’       const trimmed = line.trim();\n   231â†’       return trimmed === \"\" || !passesHardFilters(trimmed) || isSectionLabel(trimmed);\n   232â†’     });\n   233â†’   ```\n   234â†’\n   235â†’   The addition of `isSectionLabel(trimmed)` catches cases where a section label\n   236â†’   passes hard filters at an earlier iteration's filter set but was added to\n   237â†’   `SECTION_LABELS` later without being added to `passesHardFilters`. (Currently\n   238â†’   `passesHardFilters` does check `isSectionLabel`, so this is a safety net.)\n   239â†’\n   240â†’2. Increase the first-after-preamble bonus from +0.08 to +0.12 when the filtered\n   241â†’   preamble contained a section label or metadata line (not just empty lines). This\n   242â†’   gives stronger positional evidence that the first surviving candidate IS the title.\n   243â†’\n   244â†’   **Cross-iteration note:** Iteration 24 introduced the candidate-relative position\n   245â†’   bonus (~+0.08-0.12 for position 0 among surviving candidates). When both bonuses\n   246â†’   fire for the same candidate, the combined positional boost could reach ~+0.24.\n   247â†’   To prevent over-boosting non-title candidates: make the first-after-preamble bonus\n   248â†’   and candidate-relative position bonus partially exclusive â€” if both apply, cap\n   249â†’   their combined contribution at +0.15.\n   250â†’\n   251â†’**Expected impact:** Fixes D (3) = 3 failures. The stronger bonus pushes\n   252â†’`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce` and `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` above threshold.\n   253â†’\n   254â†’### Fix 5: Improve mid-recipe page detection (Pattern F)\n   255â†’\n   256â†’**Root cause detail:** `isTitleAbsentPage` checks if the first 3 non-empty lines are\n   257â†’all ingredients or cooking instructions. But:\n   258â†’\n   259â†’- Sweet Potato Salad: starts with ingredient lines â†’ `isTitleAbsentPage` should detect\n   260â†’  this. Yet the extractor returns `آ½ red onion, thinly sliced`. This means either\n   261â†’  `isTitleAbsentPage` returned false (not all 3 lines matched), or the title-absent\n   262â†’  guard (line ~1171) didn't fully filter the result.\n   263â†’\n   264â†’  Looking at the guard: it requires `rawScore >= 0.10` AND `position <= 2`. An\n   265â†’  ingredient line at position 0-2 could survive if it has rawScore â‰¥ 0.10 â€” which\n   266â†’  shouldn't happen for ingredients, but `آ½ red onion, thinly sliced` might be short\n   267â†’  enough to have a mediocre (not terrible) embedding score.\n   268â†’\n   269â†’  **Hmm** â€” but `آ½ red onion, thinly sliced` should be caught by `looksLikeIngredient`\n   270â†’  (has `آ½` = starts with number? No â€” `آ½` is not matched by `/^\\s*(?:[-â€¢*]\\s*)?\\d/`\n   271â†’  because `آ½` is not `\\d`). This is a bug in `startsWithNumber` â€” Unicode fractions\n   272â†’  aren't matched.\n   273â†’\n   274â†’- Mushroom Risotto: starts with `Reduce heat and stir...` â€” prose body text, not\n   275â†’  ingredients. `looksLikeCookingInstruction` should catch this (starts with `Reduce`),\n   276â†’  but `Reduce` is NOT in `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`. Another missing verb.\n   277â†’\n   278â†’**Fix:**\n   279â†’\n   280â†’1. Add Unicode fraction characters to `startsWithNumber`:\n   281â†’   ```typescript\n   282â†’   function startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n   283â†’     return /^\\s*(?:[-â€¢*]\\s*)?[\\dآ½â…“â…”آ¼آ¾â…•â…–â…—â…کâ…™â…ڑâ…›â…œâ…‌â…‍]/.test(line);\n   284â†’   }\n   285â†’   ```\n   286â†’\n   287â†’2. Add missing cooking verbs to `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`: `reduce`, `bring`,\n   288â†’   `toss`, `cut`, `trim`, `shape`, `form`. Wait â€” checking line 317... `reduce`,\n   289â†’   `bring`, `toss`, `cut`, `trim`, `shape`, `form`, `scatter`, `score`, `pat`, `rub`,\n   290â†’   `skim`, `strain`, `heat`, `discard`, `rest`, `marinate`, `wrap` â€” these are\n   291â†’   ALREADY in the regex (added in iteration 24). Let me re-read...\n   292â†’\n   293â†’   Yes, line 317 includes `reduce|bring|toss|cut|trim|shape|form|scatter|score|pat|rub|skim|strain|heat|discard|rest|marinate|wrap`. So `reduce` IS covered.\n   294â†’\n   295â†’   The issue with Mushroom Risotto might be different. `Reduce heat and stir...` â€” the\n   296â†’   verb is `Reduce` which IS in the pattern. So `looksLikeCookingInstruction` should\n   297â†’   return true for this line. And `isTitleAbsentPage` checks `looksLikeCookingInstruction`.\n   298â†’\n   299â†’   Let me re-examine: the requirement is that ALL of the first 3 non-empty lines match.\n   300â†’   If one of the 3 lines is neither ingredient nor instruction (e.g., a descriptive\n   301â†’   sentence), the check fails. That's probably what's happening.\n   302â†’\n   303â†’   **Alternative approach for Mushroom Risotto:** The real fix is that when the page\n   304â†’   contains no title in the early lines AND a clear recipe title appears deep in the\n   305â†’   document (position 20+), the title likely belongs to a different recipe. The\n   306â†’   title-absent guard already filters `position <= 2`, which should prevent picking\n   307â†’   up `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` from position 20+. But the feedback says it IS\n   308â†’   being extracted â€” so maybe the `titleAbsent` flag isn't being set.\n   309â†’\n   310â†’   **Fix for `isTitleAbsentPage`:** Add body-prose detection alongside ingredient\n   311â†’   and cooking-instruction checks. A line starting with a lowercase letter and having\n   312â†’   4+ words is prose continuation, not a title:\n   313â†’\n   314â†’   ```typescript\n   315â†’   function isBodyProse(line: string): boolean {\n   316â†’     return /^[a-zؤ…ؤ‡ؤ™إ‚إ„أ³إ›إ؛إ¼]/.test(line) && wordCount(line) >= 4;\n   317â†’   }\n   318â†’\n   319â†’   function isTitleAbsentPage(lines: Array<string>): boolean {\n   320â†’     const nonEmptyLines = lines.map(l => l.trim()).filter(l => l.length > 0);\n   321â†’     if (nonEmptyLines.length < 3) return false;\n   322â†’     const first3 = nonEmptyLines.slice(0, 3);\n   323â†’     return first3.every(line =>\n   324â†’       looksLikeIngredient(line) ||\n   325â†’       looksLikeCookingInstruction(line) ||\n   326â†’       isBodyProse(line)\n   327â†’     );\n   328â†’   }\n   329â†’   ```\n   330â†’\n   331â†’   Keep the strict \"all 3\" threshold (not \"2 of 3\") to minimize false positives.\n   332â†’   Recipe titles are capitalized, so lowercase start is a reliable prose indicator.\n   333â†’\n   334â†’   **Cross-iteration tension with iteration 23:** Iteration 23 added a last-resort\n   335â†’   fallback that returns the first hard-filter-passing candidate when embedding-based\n   336â†’   logic produces nothing. This pulls in the opposite direction â€” iteration 23 made\n   337â†’   the system more aggressive about returning *something*, while this fix makes it\n   338â†’   more aggressive about returning *nothing* for mid-recipe pages.\n   339â†’\n   340â†’   **Resolution:** `isTitleAbsentPage` should raise the extraction threshold (require\n   341â†’   higher rawScore + early position), NOT act as a hard gate that prevents all\n   342â†’   extraction. If `isTitleAbsentPage` is true but a position-0 candidate passes hard\n   343â†’   filters with rawScore â‰¥ 0.10, the last-resort fallback from iteration 23 should\n   344â†’   still be allowed to fire. This ensures that pages which genuinely start with a\n   345â†’   title (but happen to have body-prose-like lines nearby) aren't suppressed.\n   346â†’\n   347â†’**Expected impact:** Fixes F (2) = 2 failures.\n   348â†’\n   349â†’---\n   350â†’\n   351â†’## Summary of Changes\n   352â†’\n   353â†’### Modified file: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n   354â†’\n   355â†’| Change | Description |\n   356â†’|--------|-------------|\n   357â†’| Add common title words | ~50 words: prepositions, adjectives, short food terms |\n   358â†’\n   359â†’### Modified file: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   360â†’\n   361â†’| Change | Location | Patterns Fixed |\n   362â†’|--------|----------|----------------|\n   363â†’| Relax section-label merge block for single-word continuations | `buildCandidates`, caps-coalescing loop (~line 525) | E |\n   364â†’| Improve post-marker skip distance (marker already detected; fix skip logic) | `findBurstEnd` (~line 400) | A |\n   365â†’| Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus for section-label preambles | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` (~line 964) | D |\n   366â†’| Add Unicode fractions to `startsWithNumber` | `startsWithNumber` (~line 101) | F |\n   367â†’| Add body-prose detection to `isTitleAbsentPage` | `isTitleAbsentPage` (~line 338) | F |\n   368â†’\n   369â†’### No changes to\n   370â†’\n   371â†’- Embedding model, reference strings, or scoring formula\n   372â†’- Dedup logic (shorter-wins rule)\n   373â†’- Multi-title assembly logic\n   374â†’- Bilingual detection\n   375â†’- Threshold computation\n   376â†’\n   377â†’---\n   378â†’\n   379â†’## Testing Strategy\n   380â†’\n   381â†’### Primary validation\n   382â†’\n   383â†’Run `tools/title-loop/title-loop.py` and confirm:\n   384â†’- All 16 generated-file failures are fixed\n   385â†’- All 11 real files continue to pass (no regressions)\n   386â†’\n   387â†’### Unit test cases to add\n   388â†’\n   389â†’1. **OCR repair with common words:** Input `\"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\"` â†’\n   390â†’   repaired to `\"Braised Cod with White Wine\"`. Validates dictionary expansion.\n   391â†’\n   392â†’2. **Section-label merge in title:** Input with `LEMON HERB ROASTED` on line 1 and\n   393â†’   `VEGETABLES` on line 2 â†’ merged as `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES`.\n   394â†’\n   395â†’3. **Unicode fraction ingredient detection:** `\"آ½ red onion, thinly sliced\"` â†’\n   396â†’   `startsWithNumber` returns true.\n   397â†’\n   398â†’4. **Body-prose title-absent detection:** Input starting with `\"Reduce heat and stir...\"`\n   399â†’   followed by more body text â†’ `isTitleAbsentPage` returns true.\n   400â†’\n   401â†’5. **Spillover skip:** Input with `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]` followed by body text\n   402â†’   then a title at line 10 â†’ title correctly extracted.\n   403â†’\n   404â†’### Edge cases to verify\n   405â†’\n   406â†’- A recipe titled exactly `\"Vegetable Soup\"` where `\"VEGETABLES\"` appears on its own\n   407â†’  line â†’ should NOT be merged if preceded by 5+ word title (word count guard)\n   408â†’- A recipe starting with `\"آ½ cup\"` as the first ingredient but with a title on line 0\n   409â†’  â†’ `isTitleAbsentPage` should NOT fire because line 0 has the title\n   410â†’- Single-word section label `\"SKإپADNIKI\"` at line 2 following a complete title at\n   411â†’  line 0 â†’ should NOT merge (preceding merged text would be â‰¥5 words)\n   412â†’- Page with body prose on lines 0-2 but a valid title at position 0 that passes hard\n   413â†’  filters â†’ `isTitleAbsentPage` must NOT suppress extraction (iteration 23 last-resort\n   414â†’  fallback must still fire)\n   415â†’\n   416â†’---\n   417â†’\n   418â†’## Performance Considerations\n   419â†’\n   420â†’All changes are to string matching and heuristic checks. No additional embedding calls.\n   421â†’The dictionary expansion adds ~50 words to a Set lookup (O(1)). No performance impact.\n   422â†’\n   423â†’---\n   424â†’\n   425â†’## Security Considerations\n   426â†’\n   427â†’None. All changes are local text processing.\n   428â†’\n   429â†’---\n   430â†’\n   431â†’## Implementation Phases\n   432â†’\n   433â†’### Phase 1: Core fixes (single change set)\n   434â†’\n   435â†’1. Add common title words to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n   436â†’2. Relax section-label merge block for single-word continuations\n   437â†’3. Add Unicode fractions to `startsWithNumber`\n   438â†’4. Add body-prose detection to `isTitleAbsentPage`\n   439â†’5. Improve spillover handling in `findBurstEnd`\n   440â†’6. Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus\n   441â†’\n   442â†’All changes are independent and can be implemented in any order. Run the evaluation\n   443â†’harness once after all changes to verify.\n   444â†’\n   445â†’---\n   446â†’\n   447â†’## Risk Assessment\n   448â†’\n   449â†’| Change | Risk | Mitigation |\n   450â†’|--------|------|------------|\n   451â†’| Dictionary expansion | Over-correction: common words might cause false repairs in non-title contexts | Only triggers when word contains OCR-artifact chars; dictionary match is positive signal |\n   452â†’| Section-label merge relaxation | Could merge section labels into titles; partially reverses iteration 18/22 protections | Guarded by word count (preceding â‰¤4 words, next = single word); multi-word labels unaffected; standalone candidates still blocked |\n   453â†’| Body-prose detection in `isTitleAbsentPage` | False positives: pages with lowercase titles | Recipe titles are capitalized; lowercase start is a reliable prose indicator |\n   454â†’| First-after-preamble bonus increase | Could over-boost when combined with iter-24 candidate-relative position bonus | Cap combined positional boost at +0.15; only fires when all preceding lines were filtered |\n   455â†’\n   456â†’---\n   457â†’\n   458â†’## Open Questions\n   459â†’\n   460â†’1. **Should common title words go into `FOOD_DICTIONARY` or a separate set?**\n   461â†’   Adding to `FOOD_DICTIONARY` is simpler (one lookup). A separate set keeps the\n   462â†’   dictionary semantically focused. **Recommendation:** Add directly to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n   463â†’   â€” the dictionary's purpose is OCR repair, not food taxonomy.\n   464â†’\n   465â†’2. **Should the `isTitleAbsentPage` body-prose threshold be \"all 3\" or \"2 of 3\"?**\n   466â†’   \"All 3\" is safer (fewer false positives). \"2 of 3\" catches more mid-recipe pages.\n   467â†’   **Recommendation:** Keep \"all 3\" with the expanded detection (ingredients + instructions\n   468â†’   + body prose). If that doesn't catch all Pattern F cases, relax to \"2 of 3\".\n   469â†’\n   470â†’3. **Spillover handling: how far should `findBurstEnd` skip?** Currently it looks for\n   471â†’   the next blank line or separator after the marker. For spillover, the body text may\n   472â†’   continue for many lines without a clear separator. **Recommendation:** Skip until\n   473â†’   either (a) â‰¥2 consecutive blank lines, (b) a separator line (`====`, `----`), or\n   474â†’   (c) an ALL_CAPS line with â‰¥2 words (likely the next recipe title).\n   475â†’\n   476â†’---\n   477â†’\n   478â†’## References\n   479â†’\n   480â†’- Iteration 26 feedback: `tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/feedback.md`\n   481â†’- Iteration 25 improvement plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/25-2331e30/improvement-plan.md`\n   482â†’- Pipeline architecture: `tools/title-loop/docs/architecture.md`\n   483â†’- Accuracy history: `tools/title-loop/docs/iter.txt`\n   484â†’- Food dictionary: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n   485â†’- Title extractor: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   486â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ac2d9e1b-dbea-4db9-a94b-203c0145980c","uuid":"b5c36e45-586b-433e-a76d-615f7374459d","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/improvement-plan.md","content":"# Iteration 26 â†’ 27 Improvement Plan\n\n## Title\n\nFix generated-file title extraction: OCR repair gaps, section-label merge blocking, and spillover handling\n\n## Status\n\nDraft\n\n## Authors\n\nClaude â€” 2026-03-17\n\n## Overview\n\nIteration 26 has 0 real-file failures and 16 generated-file failures across 6 patterns.\nReal accuracy is 100% (11/11). Combined accuracy is 85.6%.\n\nThe failures share two root causes:\n\n1. **OCR repair has blind spots** â€” the food dictionary lacks common English words\n   (`with`, `the`, `and`, `dip`, `pie`), so `repairOcrWord` can't fix them. Partially-\n   repaired titles like `Braised Cod w1th White Wine` score poorly on embeddings and\n   get skipped.\n\n2. **Structural heuristics are too rigid** â€” section labels block multi-line title\n   merges even when the label is clearly a title continuation; spillover markers don't\n   trigger a wider scan; and mid-recipe pages aren't reliably detected when body text\n   precedes ingredients.\n\nThe fix addresses both causes with targeted changes: expand the OCR repair dictionary,\nrelax section-label merge blocking for title continuations, and improve spillover/\nmid-recipe detection. The pipeline architecture is unchanged.\n\n## Background / Problem Statement\n\n### Failure breakdown\n\n| Pattern | Count | Returns | Root cause |\n|---------|-------|---------|------------|\n| A. Corrupted spillover â€” title absent | 5 | empty | `findBurstEnd` skips spillover marker but doesn't scan far enough for the title |\n| B. Heavy digit corruption â€” title rejected | 2 | empty | `repairOcrText` can't fix `w1th`, `D1p` (not in food dictionary) â†’ corrupted title fails embedding scoring |\n| C. Partial corruption â€” wrong body line | 3 | wrong | Same as B â€” partially-repaired title scores lower than a body text line |\n| D. Section header before title | 3 | wrong/empty | First-after-preamble bonus isn't firing for all cases; pipe-delimited metadata followed by title not handled |\n| E. Multi-line title truncated | 1 | partial | `VEGETABLES` is in `SECTION_LABELS`, so caps-coalescing refuses to merge it with preceding `LEMON HERB ROASTED` |\n| F. Mid-recipe page start | 2 | wrong | `isTitleAbsentPage` checks first 3 lines for ingredients/instructions, but body text (prose) isn't detected |\n\n### What works well (do not change)\n\n- Pipeline architecture: candidate generation â†’ hard filters â†’ embedding scoring â†’ multi-title assembly\n- Dictionary-guided OCR repair mechanism (just needs a wider dictionary)\n- Vocabulary corroboration for multi-title assembly (iteration 25 fix)\n- Compound title dedup protection\n- Bilingual detection (both ALL_CAPS and mixed-case variants)\n- Real file accuracy: 100%\n- Shorter-wins dedup rule (DO NOT CHANGE â€” see architecture.md warning)\n\n## Goals\n\n- Fix all 16 generated-file failures without regressing real files\n- Keep changes minimal and localized within the existing pipeline stages\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Replacing the embedding model or scoring architecture\n- Reworking the overall pipeline structure\n- Adding new generated test files\n- Changing the dedup logic\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Design\n\n### Fix 1: Expand OCR repair dictionary with common English words (Patterns B, C)\n\n**Root cause detail:** `repairOcrWord` only matches against `FOOD_DICTIONARY`. Common\nEnglish words that appear in recipe titles â€” prepositions (`with`, `the`, `for`),\nadjectives (`old`, `new`, `hot`), and short food terms (`dip`, `pie`, `jam`, `bun`) â€”\nare missing. When these words contain OCR digits, repair fails and the candidate enters\nembedding scoring with residual corruption.\n\nTracing Pattern B failure `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`:\n- `Bra1sed` â†’ `braised` âœ“ (in dictionary)\n- `Cod` â†’ no digits, passes through âœ“\n- `w1th` â†’ tries `with` (1â†’i) â†’ NOT in dictionary â†’ stays `w1th` âœ—\n- `Wh1te` â†’ `white` âœ“\n- `W1ne` â†’ `wine` âœ“\n\nResult after repair: `Braised Cod w1th White Wine` â€” the residual `w1th` degrades\nembedding quality enough to push the title below threshold.\n\n**Fix:** Add a `COMMON_TITLE_WORDS` set to `food-dictionary.ts` containing ~50 words\nthat commonly appear in recipe titles but aren't food-specific:\n\n```typescript\n// Common English words that appear in recipe titles (for OCR repair)\nconst COMMON_TITLE_WORDS: Set<string> = new Set([\n  // Prepositions & conjunctions\n  \"with\", \"from\", \"over\", \"under\",\n  // Adjectives\n  \"classic\", \"simple\", \"quick\", \"easy\", \"light\",\n  \"thick\", \"thin\", \"crispy\", \"creamy\", \"spicy\",\n  // Short food terms missing from main dictionary\n  \"dip\", \"pie\", \"bun\", \"buns\", \"roll\", \"rolls\",\n  \"jam\", \"jelly\", \"tart\", \"cake\", \"loaf\",\n  \"soup\", \"stew\", \"hash\", \"bowl\", \"wrap\",\n  // Polish common title words\n  \"pieczony\", \"pieczone\", \"smaإ¼ony\", \"smaإ¼one\",\n  \"gotowany\", \"gotowane\", \"duszone\", \"duszony\",\n  \"domowy\", \"domowe\", \"tradycyjny\", \"tradycyjne\",\n]);\n```\n\nMerge this into `FOOD_DICTIONARY` (or check both sets in `repairOcrWord`). The\nsimpler approach is to add these words directly to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`.\n\n**Expected impact:** Fixes B (2) and C (3) = 5 failures. After full repair,\n`Braised Cod with White Wine` scores correctly on embeddings and wins over body text.\n\n### Fix 2: Allow section-label words in multi-line title merges (Pattern E)\n\n**Root cause detail:** In the caps-coalescing loop (line ~510-548), the condition\n`!isSectionLabel(next.text)` prevents `VEGETABLES` from merging with the preceding\n`LEMON HERB ROASTED`. But `LEMON HERB ROASTED` is clearly an incomplete title\nfragment (3 words, ends mid-phrase). The section-label check is correct in general\n(prevent merging `SKإپADNIKI` into a title), but too aggressive for single words\nthat complete an obviously truncated preceding line.\n\n**Cross-iteration tension:** Iterations 18 and 22 deliberately added `\"vegetables\"`\n(and other food-category words) to `SECTION_LABELS` to prevent standalone `VEGETABLES`\nfrom being selected as a title. This fix relaxes that protection for merges while\npreserving it for standalone candidates. The `\"placki\"` precedent from iteration 22\n(removed from `SECTION_LABELS` entirely because it starts recipe titles) shows the\nproject already acknowledges that category words can legitimately appear in titles.\n\n**Fix:** Relax the section-label merge block when the **preceding merged text** is\nshort (â‰¤ 4 words) and the next line is a single word. The heuristic: a short ALL_CAPS\nfragment followed by a single ALL_CAPS word that happens to be a section label is more\nlikely a fragmented title than a title followed by a section header.\n\n```typescript\n// In caps-coalescing loop, replace:\n//   !isSectionLabel(next.text)\n// with:\n//   !isSectionLabel(next.text) ||\n//   (wordCount(next.text) === 1 && wordCount(merged) >= 2 && wordCount(merged) <= 4)\n```\n\nAdditionally, check that the repaired form of the section label doesn't match either.\nThe existing code already checks `!isSectionLabel(repairOcrText(next.text))` â€” extend\nthe relaxation to also apply when this check would have blocked the merge.\n\n**Safety:** Only fires for single-word section labels following short ALL_CAPS\nfragments. Multi-word section labels (`SPOSOB WYKONANIA`) are unaffected. And\n`SKإپADNIKI` following a complete 5+ word title would NOT merge (the word count\nguard prevents it). Standalone `VEGETABLES` as a candidate (without a preceding\nshort fragment) is still blocked by SECTION_LABELS â€” this relaxation only applies\nto the merge path, not the standalone candidate filter.\n\n**Expected impact:** Fixes E (1) = 1 failure. `LEMON HERB ROASTED` + `VEGETABLES`\nâ†’ `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES`.\n\n### Fix 3: Improve spillover handling in `findBurstEnd` (Pattern A)\n\n**Root cause detail:** When a file starts with `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]`, the\nhard filter in `passesHardFilters` correctly rejects the spillover annotation line.\nThe `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` regex already includes `SPILLOVER` as a match, so\n`findBurstEnd` detects the marker. However, after detecting the marker, `findBurstEnd`\nlooks for a separator (blank line or `====`) to determine where the preamble ends.\nIf the spillover content continues as body text without a clear separator,\n`findBurstEnd` doesn't advance far enough. The title may be buried at line 10+ or\nabsent entirely, and the extractor gives up because no candidate emerges near the\n(insufficiently advanced) burst end.\n\n**Note (iteration 25 context):** Iteration 25 analyzed this same pattern and noted\nthat `findBurstEnd` \"doesn't skip the garbled preamble lines (they're long, not\nshort), so the proposed `i > 0` guard would never fire.\" The core issue is\nskip-distance, not marker detection.\n\n**Fix:** Two changes:\n\n1. Improve `findBurstEnd`'s post-marker skip logic. After detecting an overflow\n   marker (including `SPILLOVER`), skip ALL subsequent lines until either:\n   (a) a gap of â‰¥2 consecutive blank lines,\n   (b) a separator line (`====`, `----`), or\n   (c) an ALL_CAPS line with â‰¥2 words (structural signal for a new recipe heading).\n\n   This replaces the current \"look for next blank line\" logic which fails when\n   spillover body text continues without separators.\n\n2. In `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`, when `findBurstEnd` was able to skip a spillover\n   preamble, relax the position preference â€” don't penalize candidates at position 10+\n   just because they're far from line 0. The title position after a spillover can be\n   anywhere in the document.\n\n   Specifically: when `burstEnd > 0` and an overflow marker was detected, set the\n   position factor to treat the first post-burst candidate as position 0 for scoring.\n   This is already partially handled by the candidate-relative position bonus, but\n   `findBurstEnd` needs to actually advance past the spillover content for it to work.\n\n**Expected impact:** Fixes A (5) = 5 failures for cases where the title exists later\nin the document. For cases where the title is truly absent (was on the previous page),\nthe extractor should return empty â€” which it already does when no candidates survive.\n\n### Fix 4: Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus for Pattern D cases\n\n**Root cause detail:** The first-after-preamble bonus (line ~964-977) checks whether\nALL preceding lines were filtered or empty. For the Halibut case, `FISH & SEAFOOD`\nis filtered as a section label, so the check should pass. But the bonus is only +0.08.\nIf the actual title (`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce`) has a weak rawScore against\nthe title reference embedding (it's a mixed-case description-like string), +0.08 may\nnot be enough to clear the threshold.\n\nFor Ogأ³rkowa Zupa, the pipe-delimited metadata line is correctly filtered, and\n`OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` at position 2 should be an ALL_CAPS structural heading candidate.\nThe issue may be that `OGأ“RKOWA` contains the OCR-challenging `أ“` which could affect\nembedding quality, or that the first-after-preamble check doesn't fire because there's\na non-filtered blank line at position 1.\n\n**Fix:** Two adjustments:\n\n1. Make the first-after-preamble check more robust by also treating blank lines as\n   \"filtered\" (they already are treated as empty, but ensure the check includes them):\n\n   ```typescript\n   const allPrecedingFiltered = lines\n     .slice(0, firstCandidate.position)\n     .every((line) => {\n       const trimmed = line.trim();\n       return trimmed === \"\" || !passesHardFilters(trimmed) || isSectionLabel(trimmed);\n     });\n   ```\n\n   The addition of `isSectionLabel(trimmed)` catches cases where a section label\n   passes hard filters at an earlier iteration's filter set but was added to\n   `SECTION_LABELS` later without being added to `passesHardFilters`. (Currently\n   `passesHardFilters` does check `isSectionLabel`, so this is a safety net.)\n\n2. Increase the first-after-preamble bonus from +0.08 to +0.12 when the filtered\n   preamble contained a section label or metadata line (not just empty lines). This\n   gives stronger positional evidence that the first surviving candidate IS the title.\n\n   **Cross-iteration note:** Iteration 24 introduced the candidate-relative position\n   bonus (~+0.08-0.12 for position 0 among surviving candidates). When both bonuses\n   fire for the same candidate, the combined positional boost could reach ~+0.24.\n   To prevent over-boosting non-title candidates: make the first-after-preamble bonus\n   and candidate-relative position bonus partially exclusive â€” if both apply, cap\n   their combined contribution at +0.15.\n\n**Expected impact:** Fixes D (3) = 3 failures. The stronger bonus pushes\n`Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce` and `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` above threshold.\n\n### Fix 5: Improve mid-recipe page detection (Pattern F)\n\n**Root cause detail:** `isTitleAbsentPage` checks if the first 3 non-empty lines are\nall ingredients or cooking instructions. But:\n\n- Sweet Potato Salad: starts with ingredient lines â†’ `isTitleAbsentPage` should detect\n  this. Yet the extractor returns `آ½ red onion, thinly sliced`. This means either\n  `isTitleAbsentPage` returned false (not all 3 lines matched), or the title-absent\n  guard (line ~1171) didn't fully filter the result.\n\n  Looking at the guard: it requires `rawScore >= 0.10` AND `position <= 2`. An\n  ingredient line at position 0-2 could survive if it has rawScore â‰¥ 0.10 â€” which\n  shouldn't happen for ingredients, but `آ½ red onion, thinly sliced` might be short\n  enough to have a mediocre (not terrible) embedding score.\n\n  **Hmm** â€” but `آ½ red onion, thinly sliced` should be caught by `looksLikeIngredient`\n  (has `آ½` = starts with number? No â€” `آ½` is not matched by `/^\\s*(?:[-â€¢*]\\s*)?\\d/`\n  because `آ½` is not `\\d`). This is a bug in `startsWithNumber` â€” Unicode fractions\n  aren't matched.\n\n- Mushroom Risotto: starts with `Reduce heat and stir...` â€” prose body text, not\n  ingredients. `looksLikeCookingInstruction` should catch this (starts with `Reduce`),\n  but `Reduce` is NOT in `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`. Another missing verb.\n\n**Fix:**\n\n1. Add Unicode fraction characters to `startsWithNumber`:\n   ```typescript\n   function startsWithNumber(line: string): boolean {\n     return /^\\s*(?:[-â€¢*]\\s*)?[\\dآ½â…“â…”آ¼آ¾â…•â…–â…—â…کâ…™â…ڑâ…›â…œâ…‌â…‍]/.test(line);\n   }\n   ```\n\n2. Add missing cooking verbs to `COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`: `reduce`, `bring`,\n   `toss`, `cut`, `trim`, `shape`, `form`. Wait â€” checking line 317... `reduce`,\n   `bring`, `toss`, `cut`, `trim`, `shape`, `form`, `scatter`, `score`, `pat`, `rub`,\n   `skim`, `strain`, `heat`, `discard`, `rest`, `marinate`, `wrap` â€” these are\n   ALREADY in the regex (added in iteration 24). Let me re-read...\n\n   Yes, line 317 includes `reduce|bring|toss|cut|trim|shape|form|scatter|score|pat|rub|skim|strain|heat|discard|rest|marinate|wrap`. So `reduce` IS covered.\n\n   The issue with Mushroom Risotto might be different. `Reduce heat and stir...` â€” the\n   verb is `Reduce` which IS in the pattern. So `looksLikeCookingInstruction` should\n   return true for this line. And `isTitleAbsentPage` checks `looksLikeCookingInstruction`.\n\n   Let me re-examine: the requirement is that ALL of the first 3 non-empty lines match.\n   If one of the 3 lines is neither ingredient nor instruction (e.g., a descriptive\n   sentence), the check fails. That's probably what's happening.\n\n   **Alternative approach for Mushroom Risotto:** The real fix is that when the page\n   contains no title in the early lines AND a clear recipe title appears deep in the\n   document (position 20+), the title likely belongs to a different recipe. The\n   title-absent guard already filters `position <= 2`, which should prevent picking\n   up `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA` from position 20+. But the feedback says it IS\n   being extracted â€” so maybe the `titleAbsent` flag isn't being set.\n\n   **Fix for `isTitleAbsentPage`:** Add body-prose detection alongside ingredient\n   and cooking-instruction checks. A line starting with a lowercase letter and having\n   4+ words is prose continuation, not a title:\n\n   ```typescript\n   function isBodyProse(line: string): boolean {\n     return /^[a-zؤ…ؤ‡ؤ™إ‚إ„أ³إ›إ؛إ¼]/.test(line) && wordCount(line) >= 4;\n   }\n\n   function isTitleAbsentPage(lines: Array<string>): boolean {\n     const nonEmptyLines = lines.map(l => l.trim()).filter(l => l.length > 0);\n     if (nonEmptyLines.length < 3) return false;\n     const first3 = nonEmptyLines.slice(0, 3);\n     return first3.every(line =>\n       looksLikeIngredient(line) ||\n       looksLikeCookingInstruction(line) ||\n       isBodyProse(line)\n     );\n   }\n   ```\n\n   Keep the strict \"all 3\" threshold (not \"2 of 3\") to minimize false positives.\n   Recipe titles are capitalized, so lowercase start is a reliable prose indicator.\n\n   **Cross-iteration tension with iteration 23:** Iteration 23 added a last-resort\n   fallback that returns the first hard-filter-passing candidate when embedding-based\n   logic produces nothing. This pulls in the opposite direction â€” iteration 23 made\n   the system more aggressive about returning *something*, while this fix makes it\n   more aggressive about returning *nothing* for mid-recipe pages.\n\n   **Resolution:** `isTitleAbsentPage` should raise the extraction threshold (require\n   higher rawScore + early position), NOT act as a hard gate that prevents all\n   extraction. If `isTitleAbsentPage` is true but a position-0 candidate passes hard\n   filters with rawScore â‰¥ 0.10, the last-resort fallback from iteration 23 should\n   still be allowed to fire. This ensures that pages which genuinely start with a\n   title (but happen to have body-prose-like lines nearby) aren't suppressed.\n\n**Expected impact:** Fixes F (2) = 2 failures.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Changes\n\n### Modified file: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n\n| Change | Description |\n|--------|-------------|\n| Add common title words | ~50 words: prepositions, adjectives, short food terms |\n\n### Modified file: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n\n| Change | Location | Patterns Fixed |\n|--------|----------|----------------|\n| Relax section-label merge block for single-word continuations | `buildCandidates`, caps-coalescing loop (~line 525) | E |\n| Improve post-marker skip distance (marker already detected; fix skip logic) | `findBurstEnd` (~line 400) | A |\n| Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus for section-label preambles | `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` (~line 964) | D |\n| Add Unicode fractions to `startsWithNumber` | `startsWithNumber` (~line 101) | F |\n| Add body-prose detection to `isTitleAbsentPage` | `isTitleAbsentPage` (~line 338) | F |\n\n### No changes to\n\n- Embedding model, reference strings, or scoring formula\n- Dedup logic (shorter-wins rule)\n- Multi-title assembly logic\n- Bilingual detection\n- Threshold computation\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Primary validation\n\nRun `tools/title-loop/title-loop.py` and confirm:\n- All 16 generated-file failures are fixed\n- All 11 real files continue to pass (no regressions)\n\n### Unit test cases to add\n\n1. **OCR repair with common words:** Input `\"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\"` â†’\n   repaired to `\"Braised Cod with White Wine\"`. Validates dictionary expansion.\n\n2. **Section-label merge in title:** Input with `LEMON HERB ROASTED` on line 1 and\n   `VEGETABLES` on line 2 â†’ merged as `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES`.\n\n3. **Unicode fraction ingredient detection:** `\"آ½ red onion, thinly sliced\"` â†’\n   `startsWithNumber` returns true.\n\n4. **Body-prose title-absent detection:** Input starting with `\"Reduce heat and stir...\"`\n   followed by more body text â†’ `isTitleAbsentPage` returns true.\n\n5. **Spillover skip:** Input with `[CORRUPTED SPILLOVER...]` followed by body text\n   then a title at line 10 â†’ title correctly extracted.\n\n### Edge cases to verify\n\n- A recipe titled exactly `\"Vegetable Soup\"` where `\"VEGETABLES\"` appears on its own\n  line â†’ should NOT be merged if preceded by 5+ word title (word count guard)\n- A recipe starting with `\"آ½ cup\"` as the first ingredient but with a title on line 0\n  â†’ `isTitleAbsentPage` should NOT fire because line 0 has the title\n- Single-word section label `\"SKإپADNIKI\"` at line 2 following a complete title at\n  line 0 â†’ should NOT merge (preceding merged text would be â‰¥5 words)\n- Page with body prose on lines 0-2 but a valid title at position 0 that passes hard\n  filters â†’ `isTitleAbsentPage` must NOT suppress extraction (iteration 23 last-resort\n  fallback must still fire)\n\n---\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\nAll changes are to string matching and heuristic checks. No additional embedding calls.\nThe dictionary expansion adds ~50 words to a Set lookup (O(1)). No performance impact.\n\n---\n\n## Security Considerations\n\nNone. All changes are local text processing.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Phases\n\n### Phase 1: Core fixes (single change set)\n\n1. Add common title words to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n2. Relax section-label merge block for single-word continuations\n3. Add Unicode fractions to `startsWithNumber`\n4. Add body-prose detection to `isTitleAbsentPage`\n5. Improve spillover handling in `findBurstEnd`\n6. Strengthen first-after-preamble bonus\n\nAll changes are independent and can be implemented in any order. Run the evaluation\nharness once after all changes to verify.\n\n---\n\n## Risk Assessment\n\n| Change | Risk | Mitigation |\n|--------|------|------------|\n| Dictionary expansion | Over-correction: common words might cause false repairs in non-title contexts | Only triggers when word contains OCR-artifact chars; dictionary match is positive signal |\n| Section-label merge relaxation | Could merge section labels into titles; partially reverses iteration 18/22 protections | Guarded by word count (preceding â‰¤4 words, next = single word); multi-word labels unaffected; standalone candidates still blocked |\n| Body-prose detection in `isTitleAbsentPage` | False positives: pages with lowercase titles | Recipe titles are capitalized; lowercase start is a reliable prose indicator |\n| First-after-preamble bonus increase | Could over-boost when combined with iter-24 candidate-relative position bonus | Cap combined positional boost at +0.15; only fires when all preceding lines were filtered |\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. **Should common title words go into `FOOD_DICTIONARY` or a separate set?**\n   Adding to `FOOD_DICTIONARY` is simpler (one lookup). A separate set keeps the\n   dictionary semantically focused. **Recommendation:** Add directly to `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n   â€” the dictionary's purpose is OCR repair, not food taxonomy.\n\n2. **Should the `isTitleAbsentPage` body-prose threshold be \"all 3\" or \"2 of 3\"?**\n   \"All 3\" is safer (fewer false positives). \"2 of 3\" catches more mid-recipe pages.\n   **Recommendation:** Keep \"all 3\" with the expanded detection (ingredients + instructions\n   + body prose). If that doesn't catch all Pattern F cases, relax to \"2 of 3\".\n\n3. **Spillover handling: how far should `findBurstEnd` skip?** Currently it looks for\n   the next blank line or separator after the marker. For spillover, the body text may\n   continue for many lines without a clear separator. **Recommendation:** Skip until\n   either (a) â‰¥2 consecutive blank lines, (b) a separator line (`====`, `----`), or\n   (c) an ALL_CAPS line with â‰¥2 words (likely the next recipe title).\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Iteration 26 feedback: `tools/title-loop/docs/26-e8ee23c/feedback.md`\n- Iteration 25 improvement plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/25-2331e30/improvement-plan.md`\n- Pipeline architecture: `tools/title-loop/docs/architecture.md`\n- Accuracy history: `tools/title-loop/docs/iter.txt`\n- Food dictionary: `lib/text-classifier/food-dictionary.ts`\n- Title extractor: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n","numLines":486,"startLine":1,"totalLines":486}}}
