{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GJCwd5BzRAy1jXyz7xCHJH","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Iteration 29 â†’ 30 Improvement Plan\n     2â†’\n     3â†’**Status:** Draft\n     4â†’**Date:** 2026-03-17\n     5â†’**Baseline:** 91.9% combined accuracy (9 failures, all generated; 0 real failures)\n     6â†’\n     7â†’---\n     8â†’\n     9â†’## Overview\n    10â†’\n    11â†’Nine generated-file failures remain, clustered into three root causes:\n    12â†’\n    13â†’1. **Incomplete mixed-case OCR repair** â€” the blind repair path (`applyBlindOcrRepairToken`) only substitutes `1â†’i/l`, `آ،â†’i`, `â‚¬â†’e` in mixed-case context. It misses `0â†’o`, `4â†’a`, `5â†’s`, which the ALL_CAPS branch handles. This causes Pattern 7 (partial repair) and contributes to Patterns 1â€“4 where partially-repaired titles fail hard filters or score poorly.\n    14â†’\n    15â†’2. **Missing Polish cooking verb prefixes** â€” `looksLikeCookingInstruction` and `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` don't cover perfective forms like `ugotuj` (u+gotuj), `upiecz` (u+piecz), `podawaؤ‡/podaw4ؤ‡` (serve). Body lines starting with these verbs pass hard filters and can outscore the actual title.\n    16â†’\n    17â†’3. **Garbled tokens evade multi-word detection** â€” `isLikelyGarbled` catches single-word `[a-z][A-Z]` transitions (line 302) but not multi-word candidates containing such tokens. `XxYyZz salt and pepper` passes because the garbled check only fires for `words.length === 1`.\n    18â†’\n    19â†’Pattern 6 (Mushroom Risotto â€” title absent from document) is a structural/scan problem where the actual recipe title doesn't appear in the text. The extractor correctly identifies the best title-like line; it's just the wrong recipe. This is **not fixable** without external context and is excluded from this plan.\n    20â†’\n    21â†’---\n    22â†’\n    23â†’## Goals\n    24â†’\n    25â†’- Fix Patterns 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7 (8 of 9 failures)\n    26â†’- Maintain 100% accuracy on real files\n    27â†’- No regressions on currently-passing generated files\n    28â†’- Keep total extraction time under 10 seconds on device\n    29â†’\n    30â†’## Non-Goals\n    31â†’\n    32â†’- Fix Pattern 6 (title absent from document) â€” requires page-level context\n    33â†’- Change the embedding model or similarity strategy â€” MiniLM works well for the 102+ passing cases\n    34â†’- Restructure the candidate generation pipeline â€” it's architecturally sound\n    35â†’\n    36â†’---\n    37â†’\n    38â†’## Detailed Changes\n    39â†’\n    40â†’### Change A: Complete mixed-case blind OCR repair\n    41â†’\n    42â†’**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (lines 845â€“857)\n    43â†’\n    44â†’**Problem:** The mixed-case branch only handles three substitutions:\n    45â†’```typescript\n    46â†’// Current mixed-case path (lines 852-856):\n    47â†’.replace(/(?<=[a-zأ -إ¼])1/g, oneLetter)\n    48â†’.replace(/1(?=[a-zأ -إ¼])/g, oneLetter)\n    49â†’.replace(/آ،/g, \"i\")\n    50â†’.replace(/â‚¬/g, \"e\")\n    51â†’```\n    52â†’\n    53â†’Missing: `0â†’o`, `4â†’a`, `5â†’s` â€” all present in the ALL_CAPS branch (lines 879â€“884) but absent from mixed-case. This directly causes Pattern 7 (`S01e` â†’ `S0ie` instead of `Sole`) and weakens repair of Patterns 1â€“4.\n    54â†’\n    55â†’**Fix:** Add the missing substitutions with lowercase-adjacent context guards:\n    56â†’```typescript\n    57â†’// After the existing 1â†’oneLetter and آ،â†’i replacements, add:\n    58â†’.replace(/(?<=[a-zأ -إ¼])0/g, \"o\")\n    59â†’.replace(/0(?=[a-zأ -إ¼])/g, \"o\")\n    60â†’.replace(/(?<=[a-zأ -إ¼])4/g, \"a\")\n    61â†’.replace(/4(?=[a-zأ -إ¼])/g, \"a\")\n    62â†’.replace(/(?<=[a-zأ -إ¼])5/g, \"s\")\n    63â†’.replace(/5(?=[a-zأ -إ¼])/g, \"s\")\n    64â†’```\n    65â†’\n    66â†’The lookaround guards (requiring adjacent lowercase letters) prevent false positives on legitimate digits in titles like \"Variation 4\" or \"Page 50\".\n    67â†’\n    68â†’**Also update `generateBlindOcrVariants`** (lines 920â€“938): the dual-variant logic currently only varies `1â†’i` vs `1â†’l`. With `0â†’o` added, `S01e` will now produce `Sole` in a single pass (both `0â†’o` and `1â†’i` fire). No dual-variant needed for `0`.\n    69â†’\n    70â†’**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 7 directly. Strengthens repair for Patterns 1â€“4 by ensuring the blind repair path produces cleaner candidates that score better in embeddings.\n    71â†’\n    72â†’**Risk:** Low. The lookaround guards prevent over-application. The ALL_CAPS branch already applies these substitutions unconditionally.\n    73â†’\n    74â†’---\n    75â†’\n    76â†’### Change B: Expand garbled token detection to multi-word candidates\n    77â†’\n    78â†’**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `isLikelyGarbled` (lines 271â€“337)\n    79â†’\n    80â†’**Problem:** The `[a-z][A-Z]` internal transition check (line 302) only fires for single-word candidates (`words.length === 1`). Multi-word candidates like `XxYyZz salt and pepper` pass because `XxYyZz` is never checked individually for the transition pattern.\n    81â†’\n    82â†’**Fix:** Add a multi-word garbled token check alongside the existing short-word check (lines 318â€“333):\n    83â†’\n    84â†’```typescript\n    85â†’// After the existing short-word check (line 331-333), add:\n    86â†’// Multi-word candidate with a garbled token: a word with internal\n    87â†’// lowercaseâ†’uppercase transition that isn't a known camelCase pattern\n    88â†’// (e.g., \"McDonald\", \"McCormick\"). Catches \"XxYyZz\", \"UuIw\" etc.\n    89â†’const hasGarbledCamelCase = words.some(\n    90â†’  (w) =>\n    91â†’    w.length >= 3 &&\n    92â†’    /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n    93â†’    !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)  // Exempt Scottish/Irish names\n    94â†’);\n    95â†’if (hasGarbledCamelCase) {\n    96â†’  return true;\n    97â†’}\n    98â†’```\n    99â†’\n   100â†’**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 3 (إ»urek Krakowski â†’ `XxYyZz salt and pepper`). The garbage token `XxYyZz` triggers the `[a-z][A-Z]` check, causing the entire candidate to be rejected by hard filters. The clean title `إ»urek Krakowski` at position 0 then wins.\n   101â†’\n   102â†’**Risk:** Low. Legitimate recipe titles never contain camelCase words. The `Mc`/`Mac` exemption handles the only realistic edge case (e.g., \"McCormick Spice Blend\"), though this pattern is unlikely in recipe OCR.\n   103â†’\n   104â†’---\n   105â†’\n   106â†’### Change C: Expand Polish cooking verb filter\n   107â†’\n   108â†’**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` (line 346)\n   109â†’\n   110â†’**Problem:** The regex misses common perfective-prefix verbs:\n   111â†’- `ugotuj` (u+gotuj = \"cook [to completion]\") â€” causes Pattern 4 (`Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` wins)\n   112â†’- `upiecz` (u+piecz = \"bake [to completion]\")\n   113â†’- `usmaإ¼` is already covered, but `upiecz` and `ugotuj` are not\n   114â†’- `podawaj` is covered, but `podaw` without the full suffix isn't (OCR-corrupted `Podaw4ؤ‡` â†’ after repair â†’ `Podawaؤ‡`)\n   115â†’\n   116â†’**Fix:** Add missing verb forms to `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`:\n   117â†’\n   118â†’```typescript\n   119â†’// Add to the alternation group:\n   120â†’ugotuj|ugotowac|upiecz|usmaz    // perfective u- prefix forms\n   121â†’|podawa[cؤ‡]                      // infinitive form of \"serve\"\n   122â†’|zapiekaj                        // \"bake in oven\"\n   123â†’|obtocz|obtoczyc                 // \"coat/roll in\"\n   124â†’|podgrzej|podgrzewaj             // \"reheat/warm up\"\n   125â†’```\n   126â†’\n   127â†’Also add a catch-all for OCR-corrupted Polish verbs: lines ending with `4ؤ‡` (OCR for `aؤ‡`) that start with a known cooking-verb stem should be treated as cooking instructions. This can be done by adding an OCR-aware variant to the regex or by normalizing `4â†’a` before the instruction check.\n   128â†’\n   129â†’**Impact:** Fixes Patterns 2 and 4 where `Podaw4ؤ‡ ...` or `Ugotuj ...` body lines outscore the title. Once these lines are filtered as cooking instructions, they never enter the candidate pool.\n   130â†’\n   131â†’**Risk:** Low. These are unambiguous cooking verbs that never start recipe titles. `Ugotuj` is always imperative (â‰  title). `Podawaؤ‡` is always an instruction (â‰  title).\n   132â†’\n   133â†’---\n   134â†’\n   135â†’### Change D: Pre-filter OCR normalization for cooking instruction detection\n   136â†’\n   137â†’**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `looksLikeCookingInstruction` (line 348) and function `passesHardFilters` (line 385)\n   138â†’\n   139â†’**Problem:** `Podaw4ؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.` fails the cooking instruction check because `Podaw4ؤ‡` doesn't match any verb pattern (the `4` breaks the regex). The line passes hard filters and becomes a candidate. After OCR repair it might become `Podawaؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.` but by then it's already in the pool.\n   140â†’\n   141â†’**Fix:** In `passesHardFilters`, apply lightweight OCR normalization (`4â†’a`, `1â†’i`, `0â†’o`, `5â†’s`) to the text **before** checking `looksLikeCookingInstruction`:\n   142â†’\n   143â†’```typescript\n   144â†’function passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n   145â†’  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n   146â†’  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n   147â†’  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n   148â†’  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n   149â†’  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n   150â†’  // Apply lightweight OCR normalization before instruction check\n   151â†’  // so that \"Podaw4ؤ‡\" is recognized as \"Podawaؤ‡\" (cooking instruction)\n   152â†’  const ocrNormalized = text\n   153â†’    .replace(/4(?=[a-zأ -إ¼A-Zأ€-إ»])/g, (_, offset) =>\n   154â†’      /[A-Zأ€-إ»]/.test(text[offset]) ? \"A\" : \"a\")\n   155â†’    .replace(/(?<=[a-zأ -إ¼A-Zأ€-إ»])4/g, (_, offset) =>\n   156â†’      /[A-Zأ€-إ»]/.test(text[offset - 1]) ? \"A\" : \"a\");\n   157â†’  if (looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormalized)) return false;\n   158â†’  // ... rest of existing checks\n   159â†’```\n   160â†’\n   161â†’This is a targeted normalization (only `4â†’a` for now, since that's the specific failure), not the full blind repair. It runs before the instruction check so corrupted Polish verbs are correctly identified.\n   162â†’\n   163â†’**Impact:** Directly fixes Patterns 2 cases (`Podaw4ؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.` and `Podaw4ؤ‡ ciepإ‚o ze إ›mietanؤ… lub lodami.`) by preventing them from entering the candidate pool.\n   164â†’\n   165â†’**Risk:** Low. `4` adjacent to letters is almost always an OCR artifact, not a legitimate digit. Recipe titles don't contain `4` adjacent to letters.\n   166â†’\n   167â†’**Cross-iteration note:** Iteration 24 introduced dictionary-guided OCR repair as the primary approach, noting that blind substitution is ambiguous without word context. This Change D normalization is intentionally limited to the hard-filter path (not candidate text) and only applies `4â†’a` for cooking instruction detection. It should use the same substitution logic as `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (Change A) to avoid divergence between the two OCR normalization paths.\n   168â†’\n   169â†’---\n   170â†’\n   171â†’### Change E: Strengthen first-after-metadata positional bonus\n   172â†’\n   173â†’**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, first-after-preamble bonus (lines 1121â€“1149)\n   174â†’\n   175â†’**Problem:** Pattern 5 (Ogأ³rkowa Zupa) â€” the document starts with pipe-separated metadata, then a blank line, then the ALL_CAPS title. The first-after-preamble bonus fires (all preceding lines are filtered), but the bonus may not be enough to overcome a weak embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS text in the MiniLM model.\n   176â†’\n   177â†’**Investigation needed:** Confirm whether `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` is actually entering the candidate pool and what its raw embedding score is. The MiniLM model is English-centric and may score Polish ALL_CAPS titles very poorly (negative rawScore), causing them to fall below even the relaxed fallback threshold.\n   178â†’\n   179â†’**Cross-iteration context:**\n   180â†’- Iteration 8 introduced the `-0.05` rawScore floor for positions 0â€“2 specifically to prevent header/ingredient leakage into the fallback path. The rationale was: \"The -0.05 lower bound prevents candidates with actively negative signal from leaking through.\"\n   181â†’- Iteration 26 introduced a combined positional bonus cap of `+0.15` when both the preamble bonus and candidate-relative position bonus fire, to prevent over-boosting non-title candidates.\n   182â†’- Iteration 27 added the direct-successor bonus (`+0.10`) sharing the same `maxPositionalBoost` cap of `+0.15`.\n   183â†’\n   184â†’These prior decisions must be respected. Lowering the rawScore floor or raising the preamble bonus to the cap value would undermine the carefully layered bonus system.\n   185â†’\n   186â†’**Fix (two-part, conservative approach):**\n   187â†’\n   188â†’**Part 1 (preferred):** Keep the `-0.05` rawScore threshold unchanged. Instead, raise the combined `maxPositionalBoost` cap from `+0.15` to `+0.18` **only** when the candidate has pipe-separated metadata on the preceding line AND the candidate is ALL_CAPS. This provides additional headroom for the existing `+0.12` preamble bonus to stack with the candidate-relative position bonus without hitting the cap, while preserving the iteration 8 floor that guards against header/ingredient leakage.\n   189â†’\n   190â†’```typescript\n   191â†’// When computing maxPositionalBoost:\n   192â†’const maxPositionalBoost =\n   193â†’  hasPipeSeparatedMetadataPreamble && isAllCaps ? 0.18 : 0.15;\n   194â†’```\n   195â†’\n   196â†’This is a narrow, targeted relaxation: pipe-separated metadata followed by ALL_CAPS is a near-certain title pattern in Polish cookbooks, so the slightly higher cap is safe.\n   197â†’\n   198â†’**Part 2 (only if Part 1 is insufficient):** If the candidate still doesn't score high enough with the raised cap, the root cause is likely that Changes Aâ€“D (OCR repair improvements) haven't run yet â€” better OCR repair should produce a cleaner candidate that scores better in MiniLM embeddings. Re-evaluate after implementing Changes Aâ€“D before adding further positional overrides.\n   199â†’\n   200â†’**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 5. The pipe-separated metadata line is correctly filtered, and the ALL_CAPS title immediately after gets sufficient positional boost to overcome weak Polish embedding signal.\n   201â†’\n   202â†’**Risk:** Low. The rawScore floor (`-0.05`) from iteration 8 is preserved. The cap raise is narrow (only pipe-metadata + ALL_CAPS) and small (+0.03). The layered bonus system from iterations 24/26/27 remains intact â€” the preamble bonus (`0.12`) and direct-successor bonus (`0.10`) can now both contribute without being clamped at `0.15`.\n   203â†’\n   204â†’---\n   205â†’\n   206â†’### Change F: Add `(N)` trailing page/step number stripping\n   207â†’\n   208â†’**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `passesHardFilters` (line 385) or `stripPageNumber` (line 521)\n   209â†’\n   210â†’**Problem:** `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` â€” the `(38)` suffix is a page or step number that isn't caught by existing filters. This contributes to Pattern 4 where the instruction line passes filters and scores well.\n   211â†’\n   212â†’**Fix:** Add a stripping rule for trailing parenthesized numbers:\n   213â†’\n   214â†’```typescript\n   215â†’function stripTrailingPageRef(text: string): string {\n   216â†’  // \"Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)\" â†’ \"Ugotuj ziemniaky.\"\n   217â†’  // \"RECIPE NAME (p. 42)\" â†’ \"RECIPE NAME\"\n   218â†’  return text.replace(/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/, \"\").trim();\n   219â†’}\n   220â†’```\n   221â†’\n   222â†’Apply this in `buildCandidates` alongside `stripPageNumber` and `stripParentheticalGloss` (line 648). After stripping, the `isLikelyGarbled` mid-sentence-boundary check (`. ` followed by letter) won't be confused by the page ref.\n   223â†’\n   224â†’**Impact:** Minor supporting fix for Pattern 4. The main fix is Change C (cooking verb filter), but this strips noise that could affect scoring.\n   225â†’\n   226â†’**Risk:** Low. Trailing `(N)` where N is 1â€“4 digits is never part of a recipe title.\n   227â†’\n   228â†’---\n   229â†’\n   230â†’## Testing Strategy\n   231â†’\n   232â†’### Unit tests to add\n   233â†’\n   234â†’1. **Mixed-case OCR repair completeness:**\n   235â†’   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"S01e\", \"i\")` â†’ `\"Sole\"` (0â†’o + 1â†’i)\n   236â†’   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"m4ki\", \"i\")` â†’ `\"maki\"` (4â†’a)\n   237â†’   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"P5eudo\", \"i\")` â†’ `\"Pseudo\"` (5â†’s)\n   238â†’   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"test5\", \"i\")` â†’ `\"tests\"` (5â†’s at end)\n   239â†’\n   240â†’2. **Garbled multi-word detection:**\n   241â†’   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"XxYyZz salt and pepper\")` â†’ `true`\n   242â†’   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"McDonald Spice Blend\")` â†’ `false` (Mc exemption)\n   243â†’   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"إ»urek Krakowski\")` â†’ `false`\n   244â†’\n   245â†’3. **Polish cooking verb expansion:**\n   246â†’   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj ziemniaki w osolonej wodzie.\")` â†’ `true`\n   247â†’   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Podawaؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.\")` â†’ `true`\n   248â†’   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj\")` â†’ `false` (< 4 words)\n   249â†’\n   250â†’4. **OCR-normalized instruction detection:**\n   251â†’   - `passesHardFilters(\"Podaw4ؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.\")` â†’ `false` (cooking instruction after OCR norm)\n   252â†’\n   253â†’### Integration tests (eval loop)\n   254â†’\n   255â†’Run the full evaluation suite against all 111 test files. Expected outcomes:\n   256â†’- 0 regressions on currently-passing files\n   257â†’- 8 newly-passing files (all except Mushroom Risotto)\n   258â†’- Target: â‰¥99% combined accuracy (â‰¤2 failures)\n   259â†’\n   260â†’---\n   261â†’\n   262â†’## Performance Considerations\n   263â†’\n   264â†’All changes are O(1) per candidate (regex replacements, string checks). No additional embedding calls. No new async operations. Total impact on extraction time: negligible (< 1ms).\n   265â†’\n   266â†’---\n   267â†’\n   268â†’## Implementation Order\n   269â†’\n   270â†’Changes are independent and can be implemented in any order. However, the recommended order maximizes incremental testability:\n   271â†’\n   272â†’1. **Change B** (garbled multi-word) â€” simplest, one check addition, fixes Pattern 3\n   273â†’2. **Change C** (Polish verbs) â€” small regex expansion, fixes Pattern 2 partially\n   274â†’3. **Change D** (OCR-normalized instruction check) â€” completes Pattern 2 fix\n   275â†’4. **Change A** (mixed-case OCR repair) â€” addresses Patterns 1, 4, 7\n   276â†’5. **Change F** (trailing page ref) â€” minor cleanup\n   277â†’6. **Change E** (positional bonus) â€” Pattern 5, needs investigation if still needed after Aâ€“D\n   278â†’\n   279â†’---\n   280â†’\n   281â†’## Open Questions\n   282â†’\n   283â†’1. **Pattern 5 root cause:** Is `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` actually entering the candidate pool? If the raw embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS is very negative, Change E alone may not suffice. May need to log scoring details for this specific test case during implementation.\n   284â†’\n   285â†’2. **Dictionary coverage for `with/the/a`:** The food dictionary includes `\"with\"` (line 135), so `w1th` should be dictionary-repaired to `with`. If the dictionary-guided repair already fixes most artifacts for Patterns 1â€“2, the blind repair improvement (Change A) may be redundant for those cases. But it's still needed for Pattern 7 and words not in the dictionary.\n   286â†’\n   287â†’3. **`4â†’a` lookaround precision:** The current `0â†’O` substitution in the ALL_CAPS branch uses `(?<=[A-Zأ€-إ»])0` â€” requiring adjacent uppercase. For mixed-case, should we require BOTH adjacent characters to be letters, or just one? Single-sided lookaround matches more cases but has a slightly higher false-positive risk (e.g., `m4` in an ingredient line like `300g m4ki pszenne`). However, ingredient lines are already filtered by `looksLikeIngredient`, so the risk is minimal.\n   288â†’\n   289â†’---\n   290â†’\n   291â†’## Failure â†’ Fix Mapping\n   292â†’\n   293â†’| Pattern | Failures | Root cause | Primary fix | Secondary fix |\n   294â†’|---------|----------|-----------|-------------|---------------|\n   295â†’| 1: OCR â†’ empty | 2 | Corrupted title rejected, no fallback | A (complete OCR repair) | E (relaxed fallback) |\n   296â†’| 2: OCR â†’ wrong body | 2 | Body line (`Podaw4ؤ‡...`) outscores title | C (Polish verbs) + D (OCR-norm filter) | A (better repair) |\n   297â†’| 3: Garbage â†’ wrong body | 1 | `XxYyZz` evades garbled check | B (multi-word garbled) | â€” |\n   298â†’| 4: Erratic case â†’ wrong body | 1 | `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` wins | C (Polish verbs) + A (OCR repair) | F (page ref strip) |\n   299â†’| 5: Metadata â†’ empty | 1 | Polish ALL_CAPS weak embedding | E (positional bonus) | A (may help indirectly) |\n   300â†’| 6: Title absent | 1 | Structural problem | **Not fixable** | â€” |\n   301â†’| 7: Partial OCR | 1 | `0â†’o` missing in mixed-case | A (complete OCR repair) | â€” |\n   302â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ac2d9e1b-dbea-4db9-a94b-203c0145980c","uuid":"55098f26-7bd0-4ce3-8af5-5c4bb9a279d8","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/29-e7e3098/improvement-plan.md","content":"# Iteration 29 â†’ 30 Improvement Plan\n\n**Status:** Draft\n**Date:** 2026-03-17\n**Baseline:** 91.9% combined accuracy (9 failures, all generated; 0 real failures)\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nNine generated-file failures remain, clustered into three root causes:\n\n1. **Incomplete mixed-case OCR repair** â€” the blind repair path (`applyBlindOcrRepairToken`) only substitutes `1â†’i/l`, `آ،â†’i`, `â‚¬â†’e` in mixed-case context. It misses `0â†’o`, `4â†’a`, `5â†’s`, which the ALL_CAPS branch handles. This causes Pattern 7 (partial repair) and contributes to Patterns 1â€“4 where partially-repaired titles fail hard filters or score poorly.\n\n2. **Missing Polish cooking verb prefixes** â€” `looksLikeCookingInstruction` and `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` don't cover perfective forms like `ugotuj` (u+gotuj), `upiecz` (u+piecz), `podawaؤ‡/podaw4ؤ‡` (serve). Body lines starting with these verbs pass hard filters and can outscore the actual title.\n\n3. **Garbled tokens evade multi-word detection** â€” `isLikelyGarbled` catches single-word `[a-z][A-Z]` transitions (line 302) but not multi-word candidates containing such tokens. `XxYyZz salt and pepper` passes because the garbled check only fires for `words.length === 1`.\n\nPattern 6 (Mushroom Risotto â€” title absent from document) is a structural/scan problem where the actual recipe title doesn't appear in the text. The extractor correctly identifies the best title-like line; it's just the wrong recipe. This is **not fixable** without external context and is excluded from this plan.\n\n---\n\n## Goals\n\n- Fix Patterns 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7 (8 of 9 failures)\n- Maintain 100% accuracy on real files\n- No regressions on currently-passing generated files\n- Keep total extraction time under 10 seconds on device\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Fix Pattern 6 (title absent from document) â€” requires page-level context\n- Change the embedding model or similarity strategy â€” MiniLM works well for the 102+ passing cases\n- Restructure the candidate generation pipeline â€” it's architecturally sound\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Changes\n\n### Change A: Complete mixed-case blind OCR repair\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (lines 845â€“857)\n\n**Problem:** The mixed-case branch only handles three substitutions:\n```typescript\n// Current mixed-case path (lines 852-856):\n.replace(/(?<=[a-zأ -إ¼])1/g, oneLetter)\n.replace(/1(?=[a-zأ -إ¼])/g, oneLetter)\n.replace(/آ،/g, \"i\")\n.replace(/â‚¬/g, \"e\")\n```\n\nMissing: `0â†’o`, `4â†’a`, `5â†’s` â€” all present in the ALL_CAPS branch (lines 879â€“884) but absent from mixed-case. This directly causes Pattern 7 (`S01e` â†’ `S0ie` instead of `Sole`) and weakens repair of Patterns 1â€“4.\n\n**Fix:** Add the missing substitutions with lowercase-adjacent context guards:\n```typescript\n// After the existing 1â†’oneLetter and آ،â†’i replacements, add:\n.replace(/(?<=[a-zأ -إ¼])0/g, \"o\")\n.replace(/0(?=[a-zأ -إ¼])/g, \"o\")\n.replace(/(?<=[a-zأ -إ¼])4/g, \"a\")\n.replace(/4(?=[a-zأ -إ¼])/g, \"a\")\n.replace(/(?<=[a-zأ -إ¼])5/g, \"s\")\n.replace(/5(?=[a-zأ -إ¼])/g, \"s\")\n```\n\nThe lookaround guards (requiring adjacent lowercase letters) prevent false positives on legitimate digits in titles like \"Variation 4\" or \"Page 50\".\n\n**Also update `generateBlindOcrVariants`** (lines 920â€“938): the dual-variant logic currently only varies `1â†’i` vs `1â†’l`. With `0â†’o` added, `S01e` will now produce `Sole` in a single pass (both `0â†’o` and `1â†’i` fire). No dual-variant needed for `0`.\n\n**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 7 directly. Strengthens repair for Patterns 1â€“4 by ensuring the blind repair path produces cleaner candidates that score better in embeddings.\n\n**Risk:** Low. The lookaround guards prevent over-application. The ALL_CAPS branch already applies these substitutions unconditionally.\n\n---\n\n### Change B: Expand garbled token detection to multi-word candidates\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `isLikelyGarbled` (lines 271â€“337)\n\n**Problem:** The `[a-z][A-Z]` internal transition check (line 302) only fires for single-word candidates (`words.length === 1`). Multi-word candidates like `XxYyZz salt and pepper` pass because `XxYyZz` is never checked individually for the transition pattern.\n\n**Fix:** Add a multi-word garbled token check alongside the existing short-word check (lines 318â€“333):\n\n```typescript\n// After the existing short-word check (line 331-333), add:\n// Multi-word candidate with a garbled token: a word with internal\n// lowercaseâ†’uppercase transition that isn't a known camelCase pattern\n// (e.g., \"McDonald\", \"McCormick\"). Catches \"XxYyZz\", \"UuIw\" etc.\nconst hasGarbledCamelCase = words.some(\n  (w) =>\n    w.length >= 3 &&\n    /[a-z][A-Z]/.test(w) &&\n    !/^(Mc|Mac)[A-Z]/.test(w)  // Exempt Scottish/Irish names\n);\nif (hasGarbledCamelCase) {\n  return true;\n}\n```\n\n**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 3 (إ»urek Krakowski â†’ `XxYyZz salt and pepper`). The garbage token `XxYyZz` triggers the `[a-z][A-Z]` check, causing the entire candidate to be rejected by hard filters. The clean title `إ»urek Krakowski` at position 0 then wins.\n\n**Risk:** Low. Legitimate recipe titles never contain camelCase words. The `Mc`/`Mac` exemption handles the only realistic edge case (e.g., \"McCormick Spice Blend\"), though this pattern is unlikely in recipe OCR.\n\n---\n\n### Change C: Expand Polish cooking verb filter\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS` (line 346)\n\n**Problem:** The regex misses common perfective-prefix verbs:\n- `ugotuj` (u+gotuj = \"cook [to completion]\") â€” causes Pattern 4 (`Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` wins)\n- `upiecz` (u+piecz = \"bake [to completion]\")\n- `usmaإ¼` is already covered, but `upiecz` and `ugotuj` are not\n- `podawaj` is covered, but `podaw` without the full suffix isn't (OCR-corrupted `Podaw4ؤ‡` â†’ after repair â†’ `Podawaؤ‡`)\n\n**Fix:** Add missing verb forms to `POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`:\n\n```typescript\n// Add to the alternation group:\nugotuj|ugotowac|upiecz|usmaz    // perfective u- prefix forms\n|podawa[cؤ‡]                      // infinitive form of \"serve\"\n|zapiekaj                        // \"bake in oven\"\n|obtocz|obtoczyc                 // \"coat/roll in\"\n|podgrzej|podgrzewaj             // \"reheat/warm up\"\n```\n\nAlso add a catch-all for OCR-corrupted Polish verbs: lines ending with `4ؤ‡` (OCR for `aؤ‡`) that start with a known cooking-verb stem should be treated as cooking instructions. This can be done by adding an OCR-aware variant to the regex or by normalizing `4â†’a` before the instruction check.\n\n**Impact:** Fixes Patterns 2 and 4 where `Podaw4ؤ‡ ...` or `Ugotuj ...` body lines outscore the title. Once these lines are filtered as cooking instructions, they never enter the candidate pool.\n\n**Risk:** Low. These are unambiguous cooking verbs that never start recipe titles. `Ugotuj` is always imperative (â‰  title). `Podawaؤ‡` is always an instruction (â‰  title).\n\n---\n\n### Change D: Pre-filter OCR normalization for cooking instruction detection\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `looksLikeCookingInstruction` (line 348) and function `passesHardFilters` (line 385)\n\n**Problem:** `Podaw4ؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.` fails the cooking instruction check because `Podaw4ؤ‡` doesn't match any verb pattern (the `4` breaks the regex). The line passes hard filters and becomes a candidate. After OCR repair it might become `Podawaؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.` but by then it's already in the pool.\n\n**Fix:** In `passesHardFilters`, apply lightweight OCR normalization (`4â†’a`, `1â†’i`, `0â†’o`, `5â†’s`) to the text **before** checking `looksLikeCookingInstruction`:\n\n```typescript\nfunction passesHardFilters(text: string): boolean {\n  if (text.length < 3 || text.length > 80) return false;\n  if (looksLikeIngredient(text)) return false;\n  if (startsWithNumber(text)) return false;\n  if (looksLikeMetadata(text)) return false;\n  if (isLikelyGarbled(text)) return false;\n  // Apply lightweight OCR normalization before instruction check\n  // so that \"Podaw4ؤ‡\" is recognized as \"Podawaؤ‡\" (cooking instruction)\n  const ocrNormalized = text\n    .replace(/4(?=[a-zأ -إ¼A-Zأ€-إ»])/g, (_, offset) =>\n      /[A-Zأ€-إ»]/.test(text[offset]) ? \"A\" : \"a\")\n    .replace(/(?<=[a-zأ -إ¼A-Zأ€-إ»])4/g, (_, offset) =>\n      /[A-Zأ€-إ»]/.test(text[offset - 1]) ? \"A\" : \"a\");\n  if (looksLikeCookingInstruction(ocrNormalized)) return false;\n  // ... rest of existing checks\n```\n\nThis is a targeted normalization (only `4â†’a` for now, since that's the specific failure), not the full blind repair. It runs before the instruction check so corrupted Polish verbs are correctly identified.\n\n**Impact:** Directly fixes Patterns 2 cases (`Podaw4ؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.` and `Podaw4ؤ‡ ciepإ‚o ze إ›mietanؤ… lub lodami.`) by preventing them from entering the candidate pool.\n\n**Risk:** Low. `4` adjacent to letters is almost always an OCR artifact, not a legitimate digit. Recipe titles don't contain `4` adjacent to letters.\n\n**Cross-iteration note:** Iteration 24 introduced dictionary-guided OCR repair as the primary approach, noting that blind substitution is ambiguous without word context. This Change D normalization is intentionally limited to the hard-filter path (not candidate text) and only applies `4â†’a` for cooking instruction detection. It should use the same substitution logic as `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` (Change A) to avoid divergence between the two OCR normalization paths.\n\n---\n\n### Change E: Strengthen first-after-metadata positional bonus\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, first-after-preamble bonus (lines 1121â€“1149)\n\n**Problem:** Pattern 5 (Ogأ³rkowa Zupa) â€” the document starts with pipe-separated metadata, then a blank line, then the ALL_CAPS title. The first-after-preamble bonus fires (all preceding lines are filtered), but the bonus may not be enough to overcome a weak embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS text in the MiniLM model.\n\n**Investigation needed:** Confirm whether `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` is actually entering the candidate pool and what its raw embedding score is. The MiniLM model is English-centric and may score Polish ALL_CAPS titles very poorly (negative rawScore), causing them to fall below even the relaxed fallback threshold.\n\n**Cross-iteration context:**\n- Iteration 8 introduced the `-0.05` rawScore floor for positions 0â€“2 specifically to prevent header/ingredient leakage into the fallback path. The rationale was: \"The -0.05 lower bound prevents candidates with actively negative signal from leaking through.\"\n- Iteration 26 introduced a combined positional bonus cap of `+0.15` when both the preamble bonus and candidate-relative position bonus fire, to prevent over-boosting non-title candidates.\n- Iteration 27 added the direct-successor bonus (`+0.10`) sharing the same `maxPositionalBoost` cap of `+0.15`.\n\nThese prior decisions must be respected. Lowering the rawScore floor or raising the preamble bonus to the cap value would undermine the carefully layered bonus system.\n\n**Fix (two-part, conservative approach):**\n\n**Part 1 (preferred):** Keep the `-0.05` rawScore threshold unchanged. Instead, raise the combined `maxPositionalBoost` cap from `+0.15` to `+0.18` **only** when the candidate has pipe-separated metadata on the preceding line AND the candidate is ALL_CAPS. This provides additional headroom for the existing `+0.12` preamble bonus to stack with the candidate-relative position bonus without hitting the cap, while preserving the iteration 8 floor that guards against header/ingredient leakage.\n\n```typescript\n// When computing maxPositionalBoost:\nconst maxPositionalBoost =\n  hasPipeSeparatedMetadataPreamble && isAllCaps ? 0.18 : 0.15;\n```\n\nThis is a narrow, targeted relaxation: pipe-separated metadata followed by ALL_CAPS is a near-certain title pattern in Polish cookbooks, so the slightly higher cap is safe.\n\n**Part 2 (only if Part 1 is insufficient):** If the candidate still doesn't score high enough with the raised cap, the root cause is likely that Changes Aâ€“D (OCR repair improvements) haven't run yet â€” better OCR repair should produce a cleaner candidate that scores better in MiniLM embeddings. Re-evaluate after implementing Changes Aâ€“D before adding further positional overrides.\n\n**Impact:** Fixes Pattern 5. The pipe-separated metadata line is correctly filtered, and the ALL_CAPS title immediately after gets sufficient positional boost to overcome weak Polish embedding signal.\n\n**Risk:** Low. The rawScore floor (`-0.05`) from iteration 8 is preserved. The cap raise is narrow (only pipe-metadata + ALL_CAPS) and small (+0.03). The layered bonus system from iterations 24/26/27 remains intact â€” the preamble bonus (`0.12`) and direct-successor bonus (`0.10`) can now both contribute without being clamped at `0.15`.\n\n---\n\n### Change F: Add `(N)` trailing page/step number stripping\n\n**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, function `passesHardFilters` (line 385) or `stripPageNumber` (line 521)\n\n**Problem:** `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` â€” the `(38)` suffix is a page or step number that isn't caught by existing filters. This contributes to Pattern 4 where the instruction line passes filters and scores well.\n\n**Fix:** Add a stripping rule for trailing parenthesized numbers:\n\n```typescript\nfunction stripTrailingPageRef(text: string): string {\n  // \"Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)\" â†’ \"Ugotuj ziemniaky.\"\n  // \"RECIPE NAME (p. 42)\" â†’ \"RECIPE NAME\"\n  return text.replace(/\\s*\\((?:p\\.?\\s*)?\\d{1,4}\\)\\s*$/, \"\").trim();\n}\n```\n\nApply this in `buildCandidates` alongside `stripPageNumber` and `stripParentheticalGloss` (line 648). After stripping, the `isLikelyGarbled` mid-sentence-boundary check (`. ` followed by letter) won't be confused by the page ref.\n\n**Impact:** Minor supporting fix for Pattern 4. The main fix is Change C (cooking verb filter), but this strips noise that could affect scoring.\n\n**Risk:** Low. Trailing `(N)` where N is 1â€“4 digits is never part of a recipe title.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit tests to add\n\n1. **Mixed-case OCR repair completeness:**\n   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"S01e\", \"i\")` â†’ `\"Sole\"` (0â†’o + 1â†’i)\n   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"m4ki\", \"i\")` â†’ `\"maki\"` (4â†’a)\n   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"P5eudo\", \"i\")` â†’ `\"Pseudo\"` (5â†’s)\n   - `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(\"test5\", \"i\")` â†’ `\"tests\"` (5â†’s at end)\n\n2. **Garbled multi-word detection:**\n   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"XxYyZz salt and pepper\")` â†’ `true`\n   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"McDonald Spice Blend\")` â†’ `false` (Mc exemption)\n   - `isLikelyGarbled(\"إ»urek Krakowski\")` â†’ `false`\n\n3. **Polish cooking verb expansion:**\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj ziemniaki w osolonej wodzie.\")` â†’ `true`\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Podawaؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.\")` â†’ `true`\n   - `looksLikeCookingInstruction(\"Ugotuj\")` â†’ `false` (< 4 words)\n\n4. **OCR-normalized instruction detection:**\n   - `passesHardFilters(\"Podaw4ؤ‡ letni lub chإ‚odny.\")` â†’ `false` (cooking instruction after OCR norm)\n\n### Integration tests (eval loop)\n\nRun the full evaluation suite against all 111 test files. Expected outcomes:\n- 0 regressions on currently-passing files\n- 8 newly-passing files (all except Mushroom Risotto)\n- Target: â‰¥99% combined accuracy (â‰¤2 failures)\n\n---\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\nAll changes are O(1) per candidate (regex replacements, string checks). No additional embedding calls. No new async operations. Total impact on extraction time: negligible (< 1ms).\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Order\n\nChanges are independent and can be implemented in any order. However, the recommended order maximizes incremental testability:\n\n1. **Change B** (garbled multi-word) â€” simplest, one check addition, fixes Pattern 3\n2. **Change C** (Polish verbs) â€” small regex expansion, fixes Pattern 2 partially\n3. **Change D** (OCR-normalized instruction check) â€” completes Pattern 2 fix\n4. **Change A** (mixed-case OCR repair) â€” addresses Patterns 1, 4, 7\n5. **Change F** (trailing page ref) â€” minor cleanup\n6. **Change E** (positional bonus) â€” Pattern 5, needs investigation if still needed after Aâ€“D\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. **Pattern 5 root cause:** Is `OGأ“RKOWA ZUPA` actually entering the candidate pool? If the raw embedding score for Polish ALL_CAPS is very negative, Change E alone may not suffice. May need to log scoring details for this specific test case during implementation.\n\n2. **Dictionary coverage for `with/the/a`:** The food dictionary includes `\"with\"` (line 135), so `w1th` should be dictionary-repaired to `with`. If the dictionary-guided repair already fixes most artifacts for Patterns 1â€“2, the blind repair improvement (Change A) may be redundant for those cases. But it's still needed for Pattern 7 and words not in the dictionary.\n\n3. **`4â†’a` lookaround precision:** The current `0â†’O` substitution in the ALL_CAPS branch uses `(?<=[A-Zأ€-إ»])0` â€” requiring adjacent uppercase. For mixed-case, should we require BOTH adjacent characters to be letters, or just one? Single-sided lookaround matches more cases but has a slightly higher false-positive risk (e.g., `m4` in an ingredient line like `300g m4ki pszenne`). However, ingredient lines are already filtered by `looksLikeIngredient`, so the risk is minimal.\n\n---\n\n## Failure â†’ Fix Mapping\n\n| Pattern | Failures | Root cause | Primary fix | Secondary fix |\n|---------|----------|-----------|-------------|---------------|\n| 1: OCR â†’ empty | 2 | Corrupted title rejected, no fallback | A (complete OCR repair) | E (relaxed fallback) |\n| 2: OCR â†’ wrong body | 2 | Body line (`Podaw4ؤ‡...`) outscores title | C (Polish verbs) + D (OCR-norm filter) | A (better repair) |\n| 3: Garbage â†’ wrong body | 1 | `XxYyZz` evades garbled check | B (multi-word garbled) | â€” |\n| 4: Erratic case â†’ wrong body | 1 | `Ugotuj ziemniaky. (38)` wins | C (Polish verbs) + A (OCR repair) | F (page ref strip) |\n| 5: Metadata â†’ empty | 1 | Polish ALL_CAPS weak embedding | E (positional bonus) | A (may help indirectly) |\n| 6: Title absent | 1 | Structural problem | **Not fixable** | â€” |\n| 7: Partial OCR | 1 | `0â†’o` missing in mixed-case | A (complete OCR repair) | â€” |\n","numLines":302,"startLine":1,"totalLines":302}}}
